{"title_page": "Ranulph Crewe", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Ranulph Crewe\n|office             = [[Lord Chief Justice of the King's Bench]]\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|image              = Randolph Crewe by Peter Lely.jpg\n|caption            = Sir Ranulph Crewe, by [[Peter Lely]]\n|lieutenant         = \n|monarch            = \n|predecessor        = [[James Ley, 1st Earl of Marlborough|James Ley]]\n|primeminister      = \n|successor          = [[Nicholas Hyde]]\n|footnotes          = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|lieutenant2         = \n|monarch2            = \n|office2             = \n|predecessor2        = \n|primeminister2      = \n|successor2          = \n|party              = \n|birth_date         = 1558\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = 3 January 1645-6\n|death_place        = [[Westminster]]\n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|website            = \n|term_start         = 1625\n|term_end           = 1626\n|term_start2         = \n|term_end2           = \n|restingplace       = [[Barthomley]]\n|birthname          = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Ranulph''' (or Ralulphe, or Randolph or Randall) '''Crewe''' (or Crew) (1558 \u2013 3 January 1646) was an English judge and [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Chief Justice of the King's Bench]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nRanulph Crewe was the second son of John Crew of [[Nantwich]], who is said to have been a [[Tanning (leather)|tanner]], by Alice, daughter of Humphrey Mainwaring. He attended [[Shrewsbury School]] and, in 1576, [[Christ's College, Cambridge|Christ's College]], [[Cambridge]], but did not take a degree.<ref>{{acad|id=CRW576R|name=Crewe, Randle}}</ref><ref name=ODNB_Ranulph_Crewe>{{cite web |title = Prest W. Crewe , Sir Randolph (bap. 1559, d. 1646), in: ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (September 2004; January 2008) |url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6685 |publisher= Oxford University Press| accessdate = 2008-03-11}}</ref> He was admitted a member of [[Lincoln's Inn]] on 13 November 1577, [[Call to the bar|called to the bar]] on 8 November 1584, returned to parliament as junior member for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]], Northamptonshire, in 1597, elected a [[Bencher]] of [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1600, and [[Autumn Reader]] there in 1602. The earliest reported case in which he was engaged was tried in the Queen's Bench in Hilary term 1597\u20138, when he acted as junior to the attorney-general, [[Edward Coke|Coke]]. In 1604 he was selected by the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] to state objections to the adoption of the new style of king of Great Britain in the conference with the [[House of Lords|lords]].\n\n==Involvement in leading trials==\nHis name does not appear in the official list of returns to parliament after 1597. He was certainly, however, the member for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] in 1614, and was elected [[Speaker of the British House of Commons|speaker]] (7 April). He was knighted in June, and took the degree of [[serjeant-at-law]] in July of the following year. In the address with which, according to custom, he opened the session in 1614, he enlarged upon the length of the royal pedigree, to which he gave a fabulous extension.\n\nIn January 1614\u201315 Crewe was appointed one of the commissioners for the examination, under [[torture]], of  the [[Puritan]] minister Edmond Peacham for [[high treason]], in that his attacks, which were never published,  on the King and his ministers could be construed as incitement to [[regicide]] and [[rebellion]]. Peacham refused to speak even after being tortured on the [[rack (torture)|rack]].  Crewe concurred with the advice of the majority of the High Court judges that Peacham's unpublished writings clearly amounted to treason, although Coke in a celebrated ruling  called ''Peacham's Case'' vehemently disagreed. Peacham was sent down to [[Somersetshire]] to stand his trial at the [[assizes]]. Crewe prosecuted, and Peacham was convicted. He was sentenced to death but allowed to die in prison.\n\nCrewe's  professional reputation was somewhat damaged by the [[Leicester boy]] Witch Trials, where he sat as an extra judge of assize.  Nine women were hanged on the evidence of a young boy called John Smith  whom Crewe, and his colleague Sir [[Humphrey Winch]], found entirely credible, but whom [[James VI of Scotland|King James]] soon after declared to be a fraud.\n\nCrewe was a member of the commission which tried Richard Weston for the murder of Sir [[Thomas Overbury]] in 1615, and was concerned with [[Francis Bacon|Bacon]] and Montague in the prosecution of the [[Robert Carr, 1st Earl of Somerset|Earl]] and [[Frances Carr, Countess of Somerset|Countess]] of Somerset as accessories before the fact  to Overbury's  murder in the following year. In 1621 he conducted the prosecution of [[Henry Yelverton (attorney-general)|Henry Yelverton]], the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|attorney-general]], for certain alleged misdemeanours in connection with patents. The same year Crewe prosecuted Sir [[Francis Mitchell]] for alleged corrupt practices in executing 'the commission concerning gold and silver thread,' conducted the impeachment of [[Sir John Bennet]], judge of the [[Prerogative court]], for corruption in his office, and materially contributed to the settlement of an important point in the law of impeachment. Edward Floyde, having published a libel on the [[Elizabeth of Bohemia|Princess Palatine]], was impeached by the [[British House of Commons|commons]], and sentenced to the pillory. The [[House of Lords|lords]] disputed the right of the [[British House of Commons|commons]] to pass sentence upon the offender on two grounds : (1) that he was not a member of their house ; (2) that the offence did not touch their privileges. At the conference which followed Crewe adduced a precedent from the reign of [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]] in support of the contention of the [[House of Lords|lords]], and the [[British House of Commons|commons]] being able to produce no counter-precedent the question was quietly settled by the [[British House of Commons|commons]] entering in the journal a minute to the effect that the proceedings against Floyde should not become a precedent. In 1624 Crewe presented part of the case against [[Lionel Cranfield, 1st Earl of Middlesex|Lionel Cranfield, earl of Middlesex]], on his impeachment. The same year he was appointed [[serjeant-at-law|king's serjeant]].\n\n==Lord Chief Justice==\n[[File:Sir Randall Crewe LCJ.jpg|thumb|left|Crewe as Lord Chief Justice]]\nThe following year (26 January 1625) he was created [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|chief justice of the king's bench]] by King [[James I of England|James I]]. On 9 November 1626, he was removed by [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] for having refused to subscribe a document affirming the legality of forced loans. All his colleagues seem to have concurred with him, but he alone was punished.\n\n===The Oxford peerage case===\nThe Crewe family is said to be among the most ancient in the kingdom, a fact the importance of which is not likely to have been underrated by Sir Ranulph, if we may judge by his eloquent prologue to the [[Earl of Oxford|Oxford]] peerage case, decided 1625, which is one of the few passages of really fine prose to be found in the Law Reports. \"Time\" he said, \"hath his revolutions, and there must be an end to all temporal things, {{lang|la|finis rerum}}\". \"Where,\" he asks, \"is [[Bohun family|Bohun]], where's [[House of Mowbray|Mowbray]], where's [[House of Mortimer|Mortimer]]? Nay, which is more and most of all, where is [[House of Plantagenet|Plantagenet]]? They are entombed in the urns and sepulchres of mortality. And yet let the name and dignity of [[de Vere family|De Vere]] stand so long as it pleaseth God.\"\n\n==Retirement==\nFrom a letter written by him to the [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] (28 June 1628) it seems that he hoped to receive some compensation through Buckingham's support. On the assassination of Buckingham (24 August 1628) Crewe urged his suit upon the [[Charles I of England|king]] himself, but without success. After the impeachment in 1641 of the judges who had affirmed the legality of [[Ship money]], [[Denzil Holles, 1st Baron Holles|Denzil Holles]] moved the [[House of Lords]] to petition the [[Charles I of England|king]] to compensate Crewe, who seems to have passed the rest of his days in retirement, partly in London, and partly at his seat, Crewe Hall, [[Barthomley]], Cheshire, built by him upon an estate said to have belonged to his ancestors, which he purchased from [[Edward Coke|Coke]] in 1608. Crewe Hall was garrisoned for the parliament, taken by Byron in December 1643, and retaken in the following February. A letter from Crewe to Sir Richard Browne at Paris, under date 10 April 1644, describing the growing exasperation of 'this plus quam civile bellum,' as he called it, and the devastation of the country, is preserved in the British Museum, and is printed in the Fairfax Correspondence. Crewe died at Westminster on 3 January 1645\u20136, and was buried on 5 June in a chapel built by himself at [[Barthomley]].\n\n==Private life==\n[[File:Julia Fasey, Lady Crewe by Peter Lely.jpg|thumb|Crewe's second wife, Julia Fasey ([[Peter Lely]])]]\nHe married twice:\n#on 20 July 1598, Julia, daughter and coheiress of John Clipsby or Clippesby of Clippesby, Norfolk, who died on 29 July 1603 ;\n#on 12 April 1607, Julia, daughter of Edward Fasey of London, relict of Sir Thomas Hesketh, knight, who died on 10 August 1629. Julia Fasey was the widow of a prosperous [[Gray's Inn]] lawyer with a flourishing practise. It enabled Ranulph  to buy an estate at Barthomley  in Cheshire from Sir  [[Christopher Hatton]].<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/en/catalogues/ecatalogue.html/2009/old-master-early-british-paintings-l09631#/r=/en/ecat.fhtml.L09631.html+r.m=/en/ecat.lot.L09631.html/34/ Catalogue Note from the portraits of Randlph and Julia Crewe]</ref>\n\nBy his first wife, he had two sons, [[Clipsby Crew]] and [[John Crew]],  who were both MPs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Attribution\n*{{DNB|wstitle=Crew, Ranulphe}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]]| before=[[Edward Phelips (speaker)|Sir Edward Phelips]] | after=[[Thomas Richardson (judge)|Sir Thomas Richardson]] | years=1614}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crewe, Ranulph}}\n[[Category:1558 births]]\n[[Category:1646 deaths]]\n[[Category:Lord Chief Justices of England and Wales]]\n[[Category:People educated at Shrewsbury School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Commons of England]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1597\u20131598]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1614]]\n[[Category:16th-century English judges]]\n[[Category:16th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Serjeants-at-law (England)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Ranulph Crewe\n|office             = [[Lord Chief Justice of the King's Bench]]\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|image              = Randolph Crewe by Peter Lely.jpg\n|caption            = Sir Ranulph Crewe, by [[Peter Lely]]\n|lieutenant         = \n|monarch            = \n|predecessor        = [[James Ley, 1st Earl of Marlborough|James Ley]]\n|primeminister      = \n|successor          = [[Nicholas Hyde]]\n|footnotes          = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|lieutenant2         = \n|monarch2            = \n|office2             = \n|predecessor2        = \n|primeminister2      = \n|successor2          = \n|party              = \n|birth_date         = 1558\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = 3 January 1645-6\n|death_place        = [[Westminster]]\n|citizenship        = \n|nationality        = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = \n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = \n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = [[Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|website            = \n|term_start         = 1625\n|term_end           = 1626\n|term_start2         = \n|term_end2           = \n|restingplace       = [[Barthomley]]\n|birthname          = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Ranulph''' (or Ralulphe, or Randolph or Randall) '''Crewe''' (or Crew) (1558 \u2013 3 January 1646) was an English judge and [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Chief Justice of the King\u2019s Bench]].\n\n==Early life and career==\nRanulph Crewe was the second son of John Crew of [[Nantwich]], who is said to have been a [[Tanning (leather)|tanner]], by Alice, daughter of Humphrey Mainwaring. He attended [[Shrewsbury School]] and, in 1576, [[Christ's College, Cambridge|Christ's College]], [[Cambridge]], but did not take a degree.<ref>{{acad|id=CRW576R|name=Crewe, Randle}}</ref><ref name=ODNB_Ranulph_Crewe>{{cite web |title = Prest W. Crewe , Sir Randolph (bap. 1559, d. 1646), in: ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' (September 2004; January 2008) |url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/6685 |publisher= Oxford University Press| accessdate = 2008-03-11}}</ref> He was admitted a member of [[Lincoln's Inn]] on 13 November 1577, [[Call to the bar|called to the bar]] on 8 November 1584, returned to parliament as junior member for [[Brackley (UK Parliament constituency)|Brackley]], Northamptonshire, in 1597, elected a [[Bencher]] of [[Lincoln's Inn]] in 1600, and [[Autumn Reader]] there in 1602. The earliest reported case in which he was engaged was tried in the Queen's Bench in Hilary term 1597\u20138, when he acted as junior to the attorney-general, [[Edward Coke|Coke]]. In 1604 he was selected by the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] to state objections to the adoption of the new style of king of Great Britain in the conference with the [[House of Lords|lords]].\n\n==Involvement in leading trials==\nHis name does not appear in the official list of returns to parliament after 1597. He was certainly, however, the member for [[Saltash (UK Parliament constituency)|Saltash]] in 1614, and was elected [[Speaker of the British House of Commons|speaker]] (7 April). He was knighted in June, and took the degree of [[serjeant-at-law]] in July of the following year. In the address with which, according to custom, he opened the session in 1614, he enlarged upon the length of the royal pedigree, to which he gave a fabulous extension.\n\nIn January 1614\u201315 Crewe was appointed one of the commissioners for the examination, under [[torture]], of  the [[Puritan]] minister Edmond Peacham for [[high treason]], in that his attacks, which were never published,  on the King and his ministers could be construed as incitement to [[regicide]] and [[rebellion]]. Peacham refused to speak even after being tortured on the [[rack (torture)|rack]].  Crewe concurred with the advice of the majority of the High Court judges that Peacham's unpublished writings clearly amounted to treason, although Coke in a celebrated ruling  called ''Peacham's Case'' vehemently disagreed. Peacham was sent down to [[Somersetshire]] to stand his trial at the [[assizes]]. Crewe prosecuted, and Peacham was convicted. He was sentenced to death but allowed to die in prison.\n\nCrewe's  professional reputation was somewhat damaged by the [[Leicester boy]] Witch Trials, where he sat as an extra judge of assize.  Nine women were hanged on the evidence of a young boy called John Smith  whom Crewe, and his colleague Sir [[Humphrey Winch]], found entirely credible, but whom [[James VI of Scotland|King James]] soon after declared to be a fraud.\n\nCrewe was a member of the commission which tried Richard Weston for the murder of Sir [[Thomas Overbury]] in 1615, and was concerned with [[Francis Bacon|Bacon]] and Montague in the prosecution of the [[Robert Carr, 1st Earl of Somerset|Earl]] and [[Frances Carr, Countess of Somerset|Countess]] of Somerset as accessories before the fact  to Overbury's  murder in the following year. In 1621 he conducted the prosecution of [[Henry Yelverton (attorney-general)|Henry Yelverton]], the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|attorney-general]], for certain alleged misdemeanours in connection with patents. The same year Crewe prosecuted Sir [[Francis Mitchell]] for alleged corrupt practices in executing 'the commission concerning gold and silver thread,' conducted the impeachment of [[Sir John Bennet]], judge of the [[Prerogative court]], for corruption in his office, and materially contributed to the settlement of an important point in the law of impeachment. Edward Floyde, having published a libel on the [[Elizabeth of Bohemia|Princess Palatine]], was impeached by the [[British House of Commons|commons]], and sentenced to the pillory. The [[House of Lords|lords]] disputed the right of the [[British House of Commons|commons]] to pass sentence upon the offender on two grounds : (1) that he was not a member of their house ; (2) that the offence did not touch their privileges. At the conference which followed Crewe adduced a precedent from the reign of [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]] in support of the contention of the [[House of Lords|lords]], and the [[British House of Commons|commons]] being able to produce no counter-precedent the question was quietly settled by the [[British House of Commons|commons]] entering in the journal a minute to the effect that the proceedings against Floyde should not become a precedent. In 1624 Crewe presented part of the case against [[Lionel Cranfield, 1st Earl of Middlesex|Lionel Cranfield, earl of Middlesex]], on his impeachment. The same year he was appointed [[serjeant-at-law|king's serjeant]].\n\n==Lord Chief Justice==\n[[File:Sir Randall Crewe LCJ.jpg|thumb|left|Crewe as Lord Chief Justice]]\nThe following year (26 January 1625) he was created [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|chief justice of the king's bench]] by King [[James I of England|James I]]. On 9 November 1626, he was removed by [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] for having refused to subscribe a document affirming the legality of forced loans. All his colleagues seem to have concurred with him, but he alone was punished.\n\n===The Oxford peerage case===\nThe Crewe family is said to be among the most ancient in the kingdom, a fact the importance of which is not likely to have been underrated by Sir Ranulph, if we may judge by his eloquent prologue to the [[Earl of Oxford|Oxford]] peerage case, decided 1625, which is one of the few passages of really fine prose to be found in the Law Reports. \"Time\" he said, \"hath his revolutions, and there must be an end to all temporal things, {{lang|la|finis rerum}}\". \"Where,\" he asks, \"is [[Bohun family|Bohun]], where's [[House of Mowbray|Mowbray]], where's [[House of Mortimer|Mortimer]]? Nay, which is more and most of all, where is [[House of Plantagenet|Plantagenet]]? They are entombed in the urns and sepulchres of mortality. And yet let the name and dignity of [[de Vere family|De Vere]] stand so long as it pleaseth God.\"\n\n==Retirement==\nFrom a letter written by him to the [[George Villiers, 1st Duke of Buckingham|Duke of Buckingham]] (28 June 1628) it seems that he hoped to receive some compensation through Buckingham's support. On the assassination of Buckingham (24 August 1628) Crewe urged his suit upon the [[Charles I of England|king]] himself, but without success. After the impeachment in 1641 of the judges who had affirmed the legality of [[Ship money]], [[Denzil Holles, 1st Baron Holles|Denzil Holles]] moved the [[House of Lords]] to petition the [[Charles I of England|king]] to compensate Crewe, who seems to have passed the rest of his days in retirement, partly in London, and partly at his seat, Crewe Hall, [[Barthomley]], Cheshire, built by him upon an estate said to have belonged to his ancestors, which he purchased from [[Edward Coke|Coke]] in 1608. Crewe Hall was garrisoned for the parliament, taken by Byron in December 1643, and retaken in the following February. A letter from Crewe to Sir Richard Browne at Paris, under date 10 April 1644, describing the growing exasperation of 'this plus quam civile bellum,' as he called it, and the devastation of the country, is preserved in the British Museum, and is printed in the Fairfax Correspondence. Crewe died at Westminster on 3 January 1645-6, and was buried on 5 June in a chapel built by himself at [[Barthomley]].\n\n==Private life==\n[[File:Julia Fasey, Lady Crewe by Peter Lely.jpg|thumb|Crewe's second wife, Julia Fasey ([[Peter Lely]])]]\nHe married twice:\n#on 20 July 1598, Julia, daughter and coheiress of John Clipsby or Clippesby of Clippesby, Norfolk, who died on 29 July 1603 ;\n#on 12 April 1607, Julia, daughter of Edward Fasey of London, relict of Sir Thomas Hesketh, knight, who died on 10 August 1629. Julia Fasey was the widow of a prosperous [[Gray's Inn]] lawyer with a flourishing practise. It enabled Ranulph  to buy an estate at Barthomley  in Cheshire from Sir  [[Christopher Hatton]].<ref>[http://www.sothebys.com/en/catalogues/ecatalogue.html/2009/old-master-early-british-paintings-l09631#/r=/en/ecat.fhtml.L09631.html+r.m=/en/ecat.lot.L09631.html/34/ Catalogue Note from the portraits of Randlph and Julia Crewe]</ref>\n\nBy his first wife, he had two sons, [[Clipsby Crew]] and [[John Crew]],  who were both MPs.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Attribution\n*{{DNB|wstitle=Crew, Ranulphe}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker of the House of Commons]]| before=[[Edward Phelips (speaker)|Sir Edward Phelips]] | after=[[Thomas Richardson (judge)|Sir Thomas Richardson]] | years=1614}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Speaker of the British House of Commons}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crewe, Ranulph}}\n[[Category:1558 births]]\n[[Category:1646 deaths]]\n[[Category:Lord Chief Justices of England and Wales]]\n[[Category:People educated at Shrewsbury School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Members of Lincoln's Inn]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the House of Commons of England]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:People of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1597\u20131598]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1614]]\n[[Category:16th-century English judges]]\n[[Category:16th-century English lawyers]]\n[[Category:Serjeants-at-law (England)]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": 