80.\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Shackleton, Salmon, Lawson of Blaby, and The Baroness Shackleton of Belgravia}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| |Ebenezer| | | | |Ebenezer=Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(1784\u20141856)}}\n{{chart|,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|Richard|Henry| | | | |Barnett| |Richard=Richard Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(1836\u20141900)|Henry=Henry Shackleton<br>(b. 1847)|Barnett=[[Barnett Salmon]]<br>(1829\u20141897)}}\n{{chart|!| | | |!| | | | |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|Ebenezer|Sir Ernest| | |Alfred| |Montague|Ebenezer=Ebenezer Shackleton|Sir Ernest=''The Explorer''<br>[[Ernest Shackleton|Sir Ernest Henry Shackleton]]<br>(1874\u20141922)|Henry=Henry Shackleton<br>(b. 1847)|Alfred=[[Alfred Salmon]]<br>(1868\u20141928)|Montague=Montague Salmon<br>(b. 1878)}}\n{{chart|!| | | |!| | |,|-|^|.| | |!}}\n{{chart|Richard|Edward|Barnett|Felix|Cyril|Richard=Richard Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(b. 1899)|Edward=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|Edward Arthur Alexander Shackleton<br>'''Baron Shackleton''']]<br>(1911\u20141994)|Barnett=Barnett Alfred Salmon<br>(1895\u20141965)|Cyril=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Cyril Salmon, Baron Salmon|Cyril Barnet Salmon<br>'''Baron Salmon''']]<br>(1903\u20141991)|Felix=Felix Addison Salmon<br>(1908\u20141969)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | |!| | |!| | | | |}}\n{{chart|Richard| | | |Moira|Vanessa|~|Nigel|Richard=Lt.-Col. Richard John Shackleton<br>(1926\u20141977)|Moira=Moira Elizabeth Frances Charkham ''n\u00e9e Salmon''<br>(b. 1932)|Vanessa=Vanessa Mary Addison Salmon<br>(d. 1985)|Nigel=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Nigel Lawson|Nigel Lawson^<br>'''Baron Lawson of Blaby''']]<br>(b. 1932)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |}}\n{{chart|Ian|~|~|~|Fiona| | | | | | | |Ian=Ian Ridgeway Shackleton|Fiona=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Fiona Shackleton|Fiona Sara Shackleton ''n\u00e9e Charkam''<br>'''Baroness Shackleton of Belgravia''']]<br>(b. 1956)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n===The Sainsburys and Havers/Butler-Slosses===\nThe titles held by members of the grocer Sainsbury family are \n* [[Alan Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury|Baron '''Sainsbury''', ''of Drury Lane in the Borough of Holborn'']] (1962); \n* [[John Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover|Baron '''Sainsbury of Preston Candover''', ''of Preston Candover in the County of Hampshire'']] (1989); and \n* [[David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville|Baron '''Sainsbury of Turville''', ''of Turville in the County of Buckinghamshire'']] (1990).\nMichael Havers was made a life peer upon being appointed to the role of Lord Chancellor under Margaret Thatcher. His sister, Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, was later made a life peer upon recommendation by the House of Lords Appointments Commission. She was the first female Lord Justice of Appeal and the first female President of the Family Division of the High Court. She also chaired part of the inquests into the death of Diana, Princess of Wales and Dodi Fayed. The titles are\n* [[Michael Havers, Baron Havers|Baron '''Havers''', ''of St. Edmundsbury in the County of Suffolk'']] (1987<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/50975/page/8059</ref>) and\n* [[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Baroness '''Butler-Sloss''', ''of Marsh Green in the County of Devon'']] (2006<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/58013</ref>).\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Sainsbury, Havers, Sainsbury of Preston Candover, Sainsbury of Turville and The Baroness Butler-Sloss}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| |John| | | | |John=[[John Benjamin Sainsbury]]<br>(1871\u20141956)}}\n{{chart|,|-|^|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|Alan| |Robert| | |Cecil| |Alan=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Alan Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury|Alan John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury''']]<br>(1902\u20141998)|Robert=[[Robert Sainsbury|Sir<br>Robert James Sainsbury]]<br>(1906\u20142000)|Cecil=[[Cecil Havers|Sir<br>Cecil Robert Havers]]<br>(1889\u20141977)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | |!| | | |,|^|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|Preston| |David| |Michael| |Elizabeth|Preston=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[John Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover|John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover''']] [[Knight of the Garter|K.G.]]<br>(b. 1927)|David=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville|David John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury of Turville''']]<br>(b. 1940)|Michael=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Michael Havers, Baron Havers|Robert Michael Oldfield Havers<br>'''Baron Havers''']]<br>(1923\u20141992)|Elizabeth=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Ann Elizabeth Oldfield Butler-Sloss<br>'''Baroness Butler-Sloss''']]<br>(b. 1933)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Sarah|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|Robert|Sarah=''The Honourable''<br>Sarah Jane Sainsbury<br>(b. 1964)|Robert=''The Honourable''<br>Robert Joseph Neville Galmoye Butler-Sloss<br>(b. 1962)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n===Hurd/Hurd of Westwell/Cowdrey of Tonbridge/Kerr of Monteviot===\nFour generations of the Hurd family have sat as Conservative MPs. The two middle generations have been given life peerages (Lord Hurd of Westwell notably serving as Foreign Secretary under Margaret Thatcher and John Major), and the youngest married the daughter of The Most Hon. the Marquess of '''Lothian''' and The Rt. Hon. the Lady '''Herries of Terregles''' in 2010. Lord Lothian also sat as a Conservative MP, and was given a life peerage upon retirement from the Commons. Despite already succeeding to his titles, he did so after the House of Lords Act 1999 removed the automatic right of hereditary peers to sit in the Lords, and so required a life peerage to be able to sit there. Lord Lothian married the 16th Lady Herries of Terregles in 1975. Her elder sister, the 14th Lady, married the cricketer Colin Cowdrey in 1985. Cowdrey was given a life peerage by outgoing Prime Minister John Major in 1997. The life peerages are\n* [[Anthony Hurd, Baron Hurd|Baron '''Hurd''', ''of Newbury in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1964)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43419/page/7261</ref>\n* [[Douglas Hurd|Baron '''Hurd of Westwell''', ''of Westwell in the county of Oxfordshire'']] (1997)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54810/page/7063</ref>\n* [[Colin Cowdrey|Baron '''Cowdrey of Tonbridge''', ''of Tonbridge in the county of Kent'']] (1997)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54842/page/8443</ref> and\n* [[Michael Ancram|Baron '''Kerr of Monteviot''', ''of Monteviot in Roxburghshire'']] (2010)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-59614-1254234</ref>\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Hurd, Hurd of Westwell, Cowdrey of Tonbridge and Kerr of Monteviot}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | |Norfolk| | | | | |Hurd|Norfolk=[[File:Coronet of a British Duke.svg|15px]]<br>[[Bernard Fitzalan-Howard, 16th Duke of Norfolk|Bernard Marmaduke Fitzalan-Howard<br>16th Duke of Norfolk]]<br>(1908\u20141975)|Hurd=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Anthony Hurd, Baron Hurd|Anthony Richard Hurd<br>'''Baron Hurd''']]<br>(1901\u20141966)}}\n{{chart| | | | | | |,|^|.| | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Cowdrey|~|14| |16|m|Kerr| |Hurd2|Cowdrey=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Colin Cowdrey|Michael Colin Cowdrey<br>'''Baron Cowdrey of Tonbridge''']]<br>(1932\u20142000)|14=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Anne Cowdrey, 14th Lady Herries of Terregles|Anne Elizabeth Cowdrey ''n\u00e9e Fitzalan-Howard''<br>14th Lady Herries of Terregles]]<br>(1938\u20142014)|16=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>Theresa Jane Kerr ''n\u00e9e Fitzalan-Howard''<br>16th Lady Herries of Terregles<br>(b. 1945)|Kerr=[[File:Coronet of a British Marquess.svg|15px]]<br>[[Michael Ancram|Michael Andrew Foster Jude Kerr<br>13th Marquess of Lothian<br>'''Baron Kerr of Monteviot''']]<br>(b. 1945)|Hurd2=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Douglas Hurd|Douglas Richard Hurd<br>'''Baron Hurd of Westwell''']]<br>(b. 1930)}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |LKerr|~|~|~|RHHurd|LKerr=''Lady''<br>Clare Therese Kerr<br>(b. 1979)|RHHurd=[[Nick Hurd|''Rt. Hon.''<br>Nicholas Richard Hurd]]<br>(b. 1962)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n===The Brookes===\nBoth Barbara and her husband Henry Brooke were given life peerages, as was their son, Peter. The titles are:\n\n* [[Barbara Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte|Baroness '''Brooke of Ystradfellte''', ''of Ystradfellte in the County of Breconshire'']] (1964)\n* [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor|Baron '''Brooke of Cumnor''', ''of Cumnor in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1966)\n* [[Peter Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville|Baron '''Brooke of Sutton Mandeville''', ''of Sutton Mandeville in the County of Wiltshire'']] (2001)\n\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor]] (1903\u20131984)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Barbara Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte|Barbara Muriel Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte]] ''n\u00e9e Mathews'' (1908\u20132000)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Peter Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville|Peter Leonard Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville]] (b. 1934)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Spencer-Churchills and the Soames===\nClementine Churchill, wife of Prime Minister Winston Churchill, was created a life peer after her husband's death. One of their daughters married Christopher Soames in 1947, who was later ennobled in like manner. The titles are:\n\n* [[Clementine Churchill|Baroness '''Spencer-Churchill''', ''of Chartwell in the County of Kent'']] (1965)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43654/supplement/4861</ref>\n* [[Christopher Soames|Baron '''Soames''', ''of Fletching in the County of East Sussex'']] (1978)\n\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]'' [[Clementine Churchill|Clementine Ogilvy Spencer-Churchill, Baroness Spencer-Churchill]] (1885\u20131977)''\n** ''[[Mary Soames|Mary Soames, Lady Soames]] ''n\u00e9e Spencer-Churchill'' (1922\u20132014)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Christopher Soames|Arthur Christopher John Soames, Baron Soames]] (1920\u20131987)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Hoggs and Boyd-Carpenters===\nAside from the hereditary [[Viscount Hailsham|Barony and Viscountcy '''Hailsham''', ''of Hailsham in the County of Sussex'']] created for [[Douglas Hogg, 1st Viscount Hailsham|Douglas Hogg]], four members of these families have been given life peerages.\n[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin Hogg, 2nd Viscount Hailsham]] [[Peerage Act 1963|disclaimed]] his hereditary peerage in 1963, allowing him to take up a seat in the [[House of Commons]]. He was later given a life peerage in 1979 when he was appointed to the role of [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]. His daughter-in-law was likewise ennobled for life as was her father. The 3rd Viscount was also given a life peerage, which enables him to sit in the House of Lords following the [[House of Lords Act 1999]], which automatically excludes most hereditary peers. The life peerages are\n* [[John Boyd-Carpenter, Baron Boyd-Carpenter|Baron '''Boyd-Carpenter''', ''of Crux Easton in the County of Southampton'']] (1972,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45663/page/5315</ref> Conservative);\n* [[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Baron '''Hailsham of Saint Marylebone''', ''of Herstmonceux in the County of Sussex'']] (1979,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/18893/page/575</ref> Conservative);\n* [[Sarah Hogg, Viscountess Hailsham|Baroness '''Hogg''', ''of Kettlethorpe in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (1995,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/53948/page/1817</ref> ); and\n* [[Douglas Hogg|Baron '''Hailsham of Kettlethorpe''', ''of Kettlethorpe in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (2015,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2418750</ref>).\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Hailsham of St Marylebone, Hailsham of Kettlethorpe, Boyd-Carpenter and Baroness Hogg}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|Quintin| |John|Quintin=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin McGarel Hogg<br>'''Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone''']]<br>''2nd Viscount Hailsham 1950\u20141963''<br>(1907\u20142001)|John=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[John Boyd-Carpenter, Baron Boyd-Carpenter|John Boyd-Carpenter<br>'''Baron Boyd-Carpenter''']]<br>(1908\u20141998))}}\n{{chart| |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Douglas|~|Sarah|Douglas=[[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Douglas Hogg|Douglas Martin Hogg<br>3rd Viscount Hailsham<br>'''Baron Hailsham of Kettlethorpe''']]<br>(b. 1945)|Sarah=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Sarah Hogg, Viscountess Hailsham|Sarah Elizabeth Mary Hogg ''n\u00e9e Boyd-Carpenter''<br>Viscountess Hailsham<br>'''Baroness Hogg''']]<br>(b. 1946)}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n{{chart/end}}\n===Rayne/Vane-Tempest-Stewart/Goldsmith===\nThe two daughters of the 8th Marquess of Londonderry connect two life peers; through marriage in one case through descent in the other. Lord Londonderry's elder daughter Lady Jane Vane-Tempest-Stewart married Sir Max Rayne in 1965. Lord Londonderry's younger daughter Lady Annabel Vane-Tempest-Stewart married Sir James Goldsmith (knighted in [[Harold Wilson|Harold Wilson's]] so-called [[1976 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours|'lavender list']]); one of their sons, Zac Goldsmith, was given a life peerage by Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] to enable him to stay on in the Cabinet after losing his [[Richmond Park (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond Park seat]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 snap General Election]]. The titles are\n* [[Max Rayne|Baron '''Rayne''', ''of Prince's Meadow in Greater London'']] (1976)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46981/page/10687</ref>\n* [[Zac Goldsmith|Baron '''Goldsmith of Richmond Park''', ''of Richmond Park in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames'']] (2020)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/3468585</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Marquess.svg|15px]] ''[[Robin Vane-Tempest-Stewart, 8th Marquess of Londonderry|Edward Charles Robert Vane-Tempest-Stewart, 8th Marquess of Londonderry]] (1902\u20141955)''\n** ''Lady'' Jane Antonia Frances Rayne, Lady Rayne ''n\u00e9e Vane-Tempest-Stewart'' (b. 1932) = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Max Rayne|Max Rayne, Baron Rayne]] (1918\u20142003)''\n** [[Lady Annabel Goldsmith|''Lady'' Annabel Goldsmith ''n\u00e9e Vane-Tempest-Stewart'']] (b. 1934) = ''[[James Goldsmith|Sir James Michael Goldsmith]] (1933\u20141997)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Zac Goldsmith|Frank Zacharias Robin Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith of Richmond Park]] (b. 1975)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Wolfsons/Rawlings===\nThe titles held by members of the Wolfson family are \n* [[Leonard Wolfson, Baron Wolfson|Baron '''Wolfson''', ''of Marylebone in the City of Westminster'']] (1985); \n* [[David Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Sunningdale|Baron '''Wolfson of Sunningdale''', ''of Trevose in the County of Cornwall'']] (1991);\n* [[Patricia Rawlings, Baroness Rawlings|Baroness '''Rawlings''', ''of Burnham Westgate in the County of Norfolk]] (1994); and\n* [[Simon Wolfson|Baron '''Wolfson of Aspley Guise''', ''of Aspley Guise in the County of Bedfordshire'']] (2010).\n{{tree list}}\n* ''Solomon Wolfson (1868 \u2013 1941)''\n** [[File:Ulster.svg|15px]] ''[[Isaac Wolfson|Sir Isaac Wolfson, 1st Bt]] (1897 \u2013 1991)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Leonard Wolfson, Baron Wolfson|Leonard Gordon Wolfson, Baron Wolfson]] (1927 \u2013 2010)''\n** ''Charles K. Wolfson (1899 \u2013 1970)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[David Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Sunningdale]] (b. 1935) ~ [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Patricia Rawlings, Baroness Rawlings]] (b. 1939)\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Simon Wolfson|Simon Adam Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Aspley Guise]] (b. 1967)\n{{tree list/end}}\nLord Wolfson of Sunningdale and The Baroness Rawlings were married in 1962. Their marriage was dissolved in 1967.\n\n==Those related by blood==\n===The Watsons of Thankerton===\nBoth William Watson (1827\u20131899) and his third son, William Watson (1873\u20131948), were high ranking judges. Each were appointed Lord Advocate, and subsequently a Lord of Appeal in Ordinary. The titles are\n* [[William Watson, Baron Watson|Baron '''Watson''', ''of Thankerton, in the County of Lanark'']] (1880)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/24838/page/2725</ref> and\n* [[William Watson, Baron Thankerton|Baron '''Thankerton''' ''of Thankerton in the County of Lanark'']] (1929).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/14545/page/467</ref>\n\n===The Barons Russell of Killowen===\nThe title was created three times for father, son and grandson, all of them at some time Lords of Appeal in Ordinary. The titles are\n* [[Charles Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''', ''in the county of Down'']] (1894);<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/26511/page/2783</ref>\n* [[Frank Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''' ''of Killowen in the County of Down'']] (1929);<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/33553/page/7453</ref> and\n* [[Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''', ''of Killowen in the County of Down'']] (1975).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46701/page/12332</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Charles Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Charles Arthur Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1832 \u2013 1900)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Frank Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Francis Xavier Joseph Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1867 \u2013 1946)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1908 \u2013 1986)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Youngers===\nAside from the hereditary [[Viscount Younger of Leckie|Viscountcy '''Younger of Leckie''', ''of Alloa in the County of Clackmannan'']] (1923), two members of the Younger family have been ennobled for life. The younger brother of the first Viscount was a Law Lord and the 4th Viscount was given a peerage in the lifetime of his father, there being no possibility of a [[writ in acceleration]] as the Viscounts have no subsidiary barony. The life peerages are\n* [[Robert Younger, Baron Blanesburgh|Baron '''Blanesburgh''', ''of Alloa in the County of Clackmannanshire'']] (1923, Law Lord)\n* [[George Younger, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie|Baron '''Younger of Prestwick''', ''of Ayr in the District of Kyle and Carrick'']] (1992, Conservative)\n{{tree list}}\n* ''James Younger''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[George Younger, 1st Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1851\u20141929)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''James Younger, 2nd Viscount Younger of Leckie (1880\u20141946)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[Edward Younger, 3rd Viscount Younger of Leckie|Edward George Younger, 3rd Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1906\u20141997)''\n***** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]], [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[George Younger, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie|George Kenneth Hotson Younger, Baron Younger of Prestwick, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1931\u20142003)''\n****** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] [[James Younger, 5th Viscount Younger of Leckie|James Edward George Younger, 5th Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (b. 1955)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Robert Younger, Baron Blanesburgh]] (1861\u20141946)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n===The Keiths===\nBoth [[James Keith, Baron Keith of Avonholm|James Keith]] (1886\u20141964) and his only son, [[Henry Keith, Baron Keith of Kinkel|Henry Shanks Keith]] (1920\u20142002), were high-ranking judges. Both were [[Senator of the College of Justice|Senators of the College of Justice]] and subsequently [[Law Lord|Law Lords]], each taking the Scottish judicial title '''Lord Keith''' in 1937 and 1971 respectively, and then taking the following titles upon being made Law Lords:\n* [[James Keith, Baron Keith of Avonholm|Baron '''Keith of Avonholm''' ''of Saint Bernard's in the City of Edinburgh'']] (1953)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40008/supplement/5921</ref> and\n* [[Henry Keith, Baron Keith of Kinkel|Baron '''Keith of Kinkel''', ''of Strathtummel in the District of Perth and Kinross'']] (1977).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47120/page/471</ref>\n\n===Morrison and Mandleson===\nBoth notable [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politicians, Herbert Morrison and his grandson Peter Mandleson were given life peerages. Morrison held the position of [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]] under [[Clement Attlee|Clement Attlee, ''later'' 1st Earl Attlee]], as well as several other Cabinet positions. Mandleson was a key figure in the '[[New Labour]]' movement and a close confidant of 'New Labour' Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]], who appointed  him to several Cabinet positions, as well as to the position of [[European Commissioner for Trade#Mandelson (2004\u20132008)|European Commissioner for Trade]]. The titles are\n* [[Herbert Morrison|Baron '''Morrison of Lambeth''', ''of Lambeth in the County of London'']] (1959)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41860/page/6942</ref> and\n* [[Peter Mandelson|Baron '''Mandleson''', ''of Foy in the County of Herefordshire and of Hartlepool in the County of Durham'']] (2008)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/58855/page/15991</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Herbert Morrison|''Herbert Stanley Morrison, Baron Morrison of Lambeth]] (1888\u20141965)''\n** ''Hon. Mary Joyce Mandleson ''n\u00e9e Morrison'' (1921\u20142006)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Peter Mandelson|Peter Benjamin Mandelson, Baron Mandelson]] (b. 1953)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===Bannerman and Michie===\nBoth John Bannerman and his daughter Ray Michie were ennobled for life. Their titles are\n* [[John Bannerman, Baron Bannerman of Kildonan|Baron '''Bannerman of Kildonan''', ''of Kildonan in the County of Sutherland'']] (1967, Scottish Liberal)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/44469/page/13287</ref>\n* [[Ray Michie|Baroness '''Michie of Gallanach''', ''of Oban in Argyll and Bute'']] (2001, Liberal Democrat).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/56281/page/8601</ref>\n\n===The Janners===\nBoth Barnett Janner (1892\u20141982) and his son, Greville Ewan Janner (1928\u20142015), served as Members of Parliament for [[Leicester West (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester West]], Greville directly following his father. They were both subsequently ennobled with life peerages, which are\n* [[Barnett Janner, Baron Janner|Baron '''Janner''', ''of the City of Leicester'']] (1970, Labour)\n* [[Greville Janner|Baron '''Janner of Braunstone''', ''of Leicester in the County of Leicestershire'']] (1997, Labour).\n\n===The Frasers===\nIan Fraser was ennobled as a Law Lord in 1975. His son, a former Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], was ennobled in [[David Cameron]]'s Resignation Honours List. The titles are\n* [[Ian Fraser, Baron Fraser of Tullybelton|Baron '''Fraser of Tullybelton''', ''of Bankfoot in the County of Perth'']] (1975, Law Lord), and\n* [[Andrew Fraser, Baron Fraser of Corriegarth|Baron '''Fraser of Corriegarth''', ''Corriegarth in the County of Inverness'']] (2016, Conservative).\n\n===Lindsay and Nicholson===\nJust under a year before succeeding to the Earldoms, Robert Lindsay (then styled ''Lord Balniel'') was given a life peerage. It is notable that he entered the House of Lords in this way, as he could conceivably have entered by [[writ in acceleration]] using one of his father's junior titles (such as the Wigan Barony, or even the Lindsay and Balniel Lordship of Parliament, with which was then styling himself). His third cousin was also ennobled for life. The titles are \n* [[Robert Lindsay, 29th Earl of Crawford|Baron '''Balniel''', ''of Pitcorthie in the County of Fife'']] (1975)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46479/page/1231</ref> and\n* [[Emma Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne|Baroness '''Nicholson of Winterbourne''', ''of Winterbourne, in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1997).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54942/page/12601</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford|David Alexander Edward Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford and 10th Earl of Balcarres]] (1871\u20131940)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[David Lindsay, 28th Earl of Crawford|David Alexander Robert Lindsay, 28th Earl of Crawford and 11th Earl of Balcarres]] (1900\u20131975)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]], [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] [[Robert Lindsay, 29th Earl of Crawford|Robert Alexander Lindsay, Baron Balniel, ''subsequently'' 29th Earl of Crawford and 12th Earl of Balcarres]] (b. 1927)\n** ''Lady Katharine Constance Nicholson ''n\u00e9e Lindsay'' (1912\u20131972)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Emma Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne|Emma Harriet Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne]] (b. 1941)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Lane-Foxes===\nThe titles held by members of the Lane-Fox family are\n* [[Felicity Lane-Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox|Baroness '''Lane-Fox''', ''of Bramham in the County of West Yorkshire'']] (1981) and\n* [[Martha Lane Fox|Baroness '''Lane-Fox of Soho''', ''of Soho in the City of Westminster'']] (2013).\n{{tree list}}\n* ''Captain Edward Lane-Fox (1874\u20131949)''\n** James Henry Lane-Fox (b. 1912)\n*** [[Robin Lane Fox|Robin James Lane Fox]] (b. 1946)\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Martha Lane Fox|Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]] (b. 1973)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Felicity Lane-Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox]] (1918\u20131988)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===Callaghan and Jay===\nBoth former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom Jim Callaghan and his eldest daughter, Margaret Jay, were ennobled. Their titles are \n* [[James Callaghan|Baron '''Callaghan of Cardiff''', ''of the City of Cardiff in the County of South Glamorgan'']] (1987); and\n* [[Margaret Jay, Baroness Jay of Paddington|Baroness '''Jay of Paddington''', ''of Paddington in the City of Westminster'']] (1992).\n\n===The Palumbos===\nBoth Peter Palumbo and his eldest son, James, were ennobled. Their titles are \n* [[Peter Palumbo, Baron Palumbo|Baron '''Palumbo''', ''of Walbrook in the City of London'']] (1991); and\n* [[James Palumbo, Baron Palumbo of Southwark|Baron '''Palumbo of Southwark''', ''of Southwark, in the London Borough of Southwark'']] (2013).\n\n===The Morrises===\nAlf Morris, his brother Charles, and Charles's daughter Estelle were all Labour Members of Parliament. Alf and Estelle were both ennobled for life, their titles being\n* [[Alf Morris|Baron '''Morris of Manchester''', ''of Manchester, in the County of Greater Manchester'']] (1997, Labour)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54915/page/11391</ref>; and\n* [[Estelle Morris|Baroness '''Morris of Yardley''', ''of Yardley, in the County of West Midlands'']] (2005, Labour)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57677/page/7919</ref> \n{{tree list}}\n* ''George Morris<ref>http://www.thepeerage.com/p63308.htm#i633078</ref>\n** ''[[Charles Morris (British politician)|Rt. Hon. Charles Richard Morris]] (1926\u20132012)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Estelle Morris|Estelle Morris, Baroness Morris of Yardley]] (b. 1952)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Alf Morris|Alfred Morris, Baron Morris of Manchester]] (1928\u20132012)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n==Those related by marriage==\n* [[Richard Llewelyn-Davies, Baron Llewelyn-Davies|Baron '''Llewelyn-Davies''', ''of Hastoe in the County of Hertfordshire'']] (1964) and\n* [[Annie Llewelyn-Davies, Baroness Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe|Baroness '''Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe''', ''of Hastoe in the County of Hertfordshire'']] (1967) married in 1943.\nAfter being widowed, Baroness Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe developed a love affair at the end of her life with [[Cuthbert Alport|Baron '''Alport''', ''of Colchester in the County of Essex'']] (1961).\n\n\n* [[Edward Castle, Baron Castle|Baron '''Castle''', ''of Islington in Greater London'']] (1974) and\n* [[Barbara Castle|Baroness '''Castle of Blackburn''', ''of Ibstone in the County of Buckinghamshire'']] (1990) married in 1944.\n\n\n* [[Mary Stewart, Baroness Stewart of Alvechurch|Baroness '''Stewart of Alvechurch''', ''of Fulham in Greater London'']] (1975) and\n* [[Michael Stewart, Baron Stewart of Fulham|Baron '''Stewart of Fulham''', ''of Fulham in Greater London'']] (1979) married in 1941.\n\n\n* [[Sue Ryder|Baroness '''Ryder of Warsaw''', ''of Warsaw in Poland and of Cavendish in the County of Suffolk'']] (1979) and\n* [[Leonard Cheshire|Baron '''Cheshire''', ''of Woodhall in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (1991) married in 1959.\n\n\n* [[Hugh Griffiths, Baron Griffiths|Baron '''Griffiths''', ''of Govilon, in the County of Gwent'']] (1985) and\n* [[Heather Brigstocke, Baroness Brigstocke|Baroness '''Brigstocke''', ''of Kensington in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea'']] (1990) married in 2000.\n\n\n* [[Geoffrey Howe|Baron '''Howe of Aberavon''', ''of Tandridge in the County of Surrey'']] (1992) and\n* [[Elspeth Howe, Baroness Howe of Idlicote|Baroness '''Howe of Idlicote''', ''of Shipston-on-Stour in the County of Warwickshire'']] (2001) married in 1953.\n\n\n* [[Diana Maddock, Baroness Maddock|Baroness '''Maddock''', ''of Christchurch in the County of Dorset'']] (1997) and \n* [[Alan Beith|Baron '''Beith''', ''of Berwick-upon-Tweed in the County of Northumberland'']] (2015) married in 2001.\n\n\n* [[Richard Layard, Baron Layard|Baron '''Layard''', ''of Highgate in the London Borough of Haringey'']] (2000) and \n* [[Molly Meacher, Baroness Meacher|Baroness '''Meacher''', ''of Spitalfields, in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets'']] (2006) married in 1991.\n\n\n* [[Robin Hodgson, Baron Hodgson of Astley Abbotts|Baron '''Hodgson of Astley Abbotts''', ''of Nash in the County of Shropshire'']] (2000)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55872 |date=12 June 2000 |page=6375}}</ref> and\n* [[Fiona Hodgson, Baroness Hodgson of Abinger|Baroness '''Hodgson of Abinger''', ''of Abinger in the County of Surrey'']] (2013)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60632 |date=19 September 2013 |page=18509}}</ref> married in 1982.\n\n\n* [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Baron '''Gould of Brookwood''', ''of Brookwood in the County of Surrey'']] (2004) and\n* [[Gail Rebuck|Baroness '''Rebuck''', ''of Bloomsbury in the London Borough of Camden'']] (2014) were married from 1985 until Lord Gould of Brookwood's death in 2011.\n\n\n* [[Neil Kinnock|Baron '''Kinnock''', ''of Bedwellty in the County of Gwent'']] (2005) and\n* [[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|Baroness '''Kinnock of Holyhead''', ''of Holyhead in the County of Ynys M\u00f4n'']] (2009) married in 1967.\n\n\n*[[Eileen Paisley, Baroness Paisley of St George's|Baroness '''Paisley of St George's''', ''of St George's in the County of Antrim'']] (2006), one of the first three members of the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] to be made a life peer, and \n* [[Ian Paisley|Baron '''Bannside''', ''of North Antrim in the County of Antrim'']] (2010), one of the founders of the party, married in 1956.\n\n==See also==\nThe title [[Irene Curzon, 2nd Baroness Ravensdale|Baroness '''Ravensdale of Kedleston''', ''of Kedleston, in the County of Derby'']] (1958) was given to Irene Curzon, 2nd [[Baron Ravensdale|Baroness '''Ravensdale''', ''of Ravensdale in the County of Derby'']] (1911) to enable her to take a seat in the House of Lords as it was only after the [[Peerage Act 1963]] that ''suo jure'' peeresses could sit in the House by virtue of their hereditary peerages. She was the eldest daughter of [[George Curzon, 1st Marquess Curzon of Kedleston|The Marquess Curzon of Kedleston]], and therefore related to not only future Barons Ravensdale, but also the Barons and [[Viscount Scarsdale|Viscounts Scarsdale]].\n\n[[Evelyn Emmet, Baroness Emmet of Amberley|Baroness '''Emmet of Amberley''', ''of Amberley in the County of Sussex'']] (1965), was the eldest daughter of [[Rennell Rodd, 1st Baron Rennell]].\n\n[[George Howard, Baron Howard of Henderskelfe|Baron '''Howard of Henderskelfe''', ''of Henderskelfe in the County of North Yorkshire'']] (1983), who was in line to succeed to the [[Earl of Carlisle|Earldom of Carlisle]].\n\n[[Hugh Cavendish, Baron Cavendish of Furness|Baron '''Cavendish of Furness''', ''of Cartmel in the County of Cumbria'']] (1990), who is in the line of succession to the [[Duke of Devonshire|Dukedom of Devonshire]].\n\n[[Greville Howard, Baron Howard of Rising|Baron '''Howard of Rising''', ''of Castle Rising in the County of Norfolk'']] (2004), who is in the line of succession to the [[Earl of Suffolk|Earldoms of Suffolk and Berkshire]].\n\n[[Eliza Manningham-Buller|Baroness '''Manningham-Buller''', ''of Northampton in the County of Northamptonshire'']] (2008), who is the second daughter of [[Reginald Manningham-Buller, 1st Viscount Dilhorne]]. The [[Viscount Dilhorne|Dilhorne Viscountcy]] is the most recently created extant one.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Related Life Peers}}\n[[Category:Life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lists of British nobility]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=June 2019}}\n\nThis is a list of people with [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|peerages of the United Kingdom]] created under the [[Life Peerages Act 1958]] and [[Judicial functions of the House of Lords|Lords of Appeal in Ordinary]] (whose life peerages are created under the [[Appellate Jurisdiction Act 1876]]) who are closely related to one another, either by blood up to the degree of third cousins, or by marriage or cohabitation. This list is ordered by the antiquity of the earliest title each family has.\n\n==Those related by blood and marriage==\n===The Asquiths/Bonham Carters===\nAside from the hereditary [[Earl of Oxford and Asquith|Earldom of '''Oxford and Asquith''', and Viscountcy '''Asquith''', ''of Morley in the West Riding of the County of York'']], members of the Asquith, Bonham Carter and related families have been ennobled with the following life peerages: \n* [[Cyril Asquith, Baron Asquith of Bishopstone|Baron '''Asquith of Bishopstone''', ''of Bishopstone in the County of Sussex'']] (1951,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/39212/page/2327</ref> Law Lord); \n* [[Katharine Elliot, Baroness Elliot of Harwood|Baroness '''Elliot of Harwood''', ''of Rulewater in the County of Roxburgh'']] (1958,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41507/page/5887</ref> Conservative);\n* [[Violet Bonham Carter|Baroness '''Asquith of Yarnbury''', ''of Yarnbury in the County of Wiltshire'']] (1964,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43522/page/10933</ref> Liberal); \n* [[Jo Grimond|Baron '''Grimond''', ''of Firth in the County of Orkney'']] (1983,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/49511/page/13655</ref> Liberal); \n* [[Mark Bonham Carter, Baron Bonham-Carter|Baron '''Bonham-Carter''', ''of Yarnbury in the County of Wiltshire'']] (1986,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/50609/page/9829</ref> Liberal Democrat); \n* [[Tim Razzall, Baron Razzall|Baron '''Razzall''', ''of Mortlake in the London Borough of Richmond'']] (1997, <ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54932/page/12093</ref> Liberal Democrat); and\n* [[Jane Bonham Carter, Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury|Baroness '''Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury''', ''of Yarnbury in the County of Wiltshire'']] (2004,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57340/page/8083</ref> Liberal Democrat).\nLord Grimond and The Hon. Laura Bonham Carter married in 1938.\nLord Razzall and The Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury became partners<ref>https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/baroness-bonham-carter-of-yarnbury/3699/register-of-interests</ref> in 2008.\n\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Ulster.svg|15px]] ''[[Sir Charles Tennant, 1st Baronet|Sir Charles Clow Tennant, 1st Baronet]] (1823\u20131906)''\n** ''[[Margot Asquith|Emma Margaret Asquith, Countess of Oxford and Asquith]] ''n\u00e9e Tennant'' (1864\u20131945)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[H. H. Asquith|Herbert Henry Asquith, 1st Earl of Oxford and Asquith]] (1852\u20131928)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Katharine Elliot, Baroness Elliot of Harwood]] ''n\u00e9e Tennant'' (1903\u20131994)''\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[H. H. Asquith|Herbert Henry Asquith, 1st Earl of Oxford and Asquith]] (1852\u20131928)''\n** ''[[Raymond Asquith|Raymond Herbert Asquith]] (1878\u20131916)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[Julian Asquith, 2nd Earl of Oxford and Asquith|Edward Julian George Asquith, 2nd Earl of Oxford and Asquith]] (1916\u20132011)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] [[Raymond Asquith, 3rd Earl of Oxford and Asquith|Raymond Benedict Bartholomew Michael Asquith, 3rd Earl of Oxford and Asquith]] (b. 1952) ''Representative peer in the [[House of Lords]] from 2014, replacing [[Robert Methuen, 7th Baron Methuen|Lord Methuen]].''\n***** Mark Julian Asquith, Viscount Asquith (b. 1979)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Violet Bonham Carter|Helen Violet Bonham Carter, Baroness Asquith of Yarnbury]] ''n\u00e9e Violet Asquith'' (1887\u20131969)''\n*** ''[[Laura Grimond|Laura Grimond, Lady Grimond]]  ''n\u00e9e Bonham Carter'' (1918\u20131994)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Jo Grimond|Joseph Grimond, Baron Grimond]] (1913\u20131993)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Mark Bonham Carter, Baron Bonham-Carter|Mark Raymond Bonham Carter, Baron Bonham-Carter]](1922\u20131994)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Jane Bonham Carter, Baroness Bonham-Carter of Yarnbury|Jane Mary Bonham Carter, Baroness \nBonham-Carter of Yarnbury]] (b. 1957) ~ [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Tim Razzall, Baron Razzall|Edward Timothy Razzall, Baron Razzall]] (b. 1943)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Cyril Asquith, Baron Asquith of Bishopstone]] (1890\u20131954)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n===The Shackletons/Salmons===\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|'''Baron Shackleton''', ''of Burley in the County of Southampton'']] (1958, Labour<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41473/page/5077</ref>)\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Cyril Salmon, Baron Salmon|'''Baron Salmon''', ''of Sandwich in the County of Kent'']] (1972, Law Lord<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45572/page/449</ref>)\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Nigel Lawson|'''Baron Lawson of Blaby''', ''of Newnham in the County of Northamptonshire'']] (1992, Conservative<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/52982/page/11339</ref>)\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Fiona Shackleton|'''Baroness Shackleton of Belgravia''', ''of Belgravia in the City of Westminster'']] (2010, Conservative<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/59664/page/133</ref>)\n^Nigel Lawson married Vanessa Salmon in 1955. They divorced in 1980.\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Shackleton, Salmon, Lawson of Blaby, and The Baroness Shackleton of Belgravia}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| |Ebenezer| | | | |Ebenezer=Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(1784\u20141856)}}\n{{chart|,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|Richard|Henry| | | | |Barnett| |Richard=Richard Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(1836\u20141900)|Henry=Henry Shackleton<br>(b. 1847)|Barnett=[[Barnett Salmon]]<br>(1829\u20141897)}}\n{{chart|!| | | |!| | | | |,|-|^|-|.}}\n{{chart|Ebenezer|Sir Ernest| | |Alfred| |Montague|Ebenezer=Ebenezer Shackleton|Sir Ernest=''The Explorer''<br>[[Ernest Shackleton|Sir Ernest Henry Shackleton]]<br>(1874\u20141922)|Henry=Henry Shackleton<br>(b. 1847)|Alfred=[[Alfred Salmon]]<br>(1868\u20141928)|Montague=Montague Salmon<br>(b. 1878)}}\n{{chart|!| | | |!| | |,|-|^|.| | |!}}\n{{chart|Richard|Edward|Barnett|Felix|Cyril|Richard=Richard Ebenezer Shackleton<br>(b. 1899)|Edward=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Edward Shackleton, Baron Shackleton|Edward Arthur Alexander Shackleton<br>'''Baron Shackleton''']]<br>(1911\u20141994)|Barnett=Barnett Alfred Salmon<br>(1895\u20141965)|Cyril=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Cyril Salmon, Baron Salmon|Cyril Barnet Salmon<br>'''Baron Salmon''']]<br>(1903\u20141991)|Felix=Felix Addison Salmon<br>(1908\u20141969)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | |!| | |!| | | | |}}\n{{chart|Richard| | | |Moira|Vanessa|~|Nigel|Richard=Lt.-Col. Richard John Shackleton<br>(1926\u20141977)|Moira=Moira Elizabeth Frances Charkham ''n\u00e9e Salmon''<br>(b. 1932)|Vanessa=Vanessa Mary Addison Salmon<br>(d. 1985)|Nigel=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Nigel Lawson|Nigel Lawson^<br>'''Baron Lawson of Blaby''']]<br>(b. 1932)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | |!| | | | | | | |}}\n{{chart|Ian|~|~|~|Fiona| | | | | | | |Ian=Ian Ridgeway Shackleton|Fiona=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Fiona Shackleton|Fiona Sara Shackleton ''n\u00e9e Charkam''<br>'''Baroness Shackleton of Belgravia''']]<br>(b. 1956)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n===The Sainsburys and Havers/Butler-Slosses===\nThe titles held by members of the grocer Sainsbury family are \n* [[Alan Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury|Baron '''Sainsbury''', ''of Drury Lane in the Borough of Holborn'']] (1962); \n* [[John Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover|Baron '''Sainsbury of Preston Candover''', ''of Preston Candover in the County of Hampshire'']] (1989); and \n* [[David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville|Baron '''Sainsbury of Turville''', ''of Turville in the County of Buckinghamshire'']] (1990).\nMichael Havers was made a life peer upon being appointed to the role of Lord Chancellor under Margaret Thatcher. His sister, Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, was later made a life peer upon recommendation by the House of Lords Appointments Commission. She was the first female Lord Justice of Appeal and the first female President of the Family Division of the High Court. She also chaired part of the inquests into the death of Diana, Princess of Wales and Dodi Fayed. The titles are\n* [[Michael Havers, Baron Havers|Baron '''Havers''', ''of St. Edmundsbury in the County of Suffolk'']] (1987<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/50975/page/8059</ref>) and\n* [[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Baroness '''Butler-Sloss''', ''of Marsh Green in the County of Devon'']] (2006<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/58013</ref>).\n\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Sainsbury, Havers, Sainsbury of Preston Candover, Sainsbury of Turville and The Baroness Butler-Sloss}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| |John| | | | |John=[[John Benjamin Sainsbury]]<br>(1871\u20141956)}}\n{{chart|,|-|^|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|Alan| |Robert| | |Cecil| |Alan=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Alan Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury|Alan John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury''']]<br>(1902\u20141998)|Robert=[[Robert Sainsbury|Sir<br>Robert James Sainsbury]]<br>(1906\u20142000)|Cecil=[[Cecil Havers|Sir<br>Cecil Robert Havers]]<br>(1889\u20141977)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | |!| | | |,|^|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|Preston| |David| |Michael| |Elizabeth|Preston=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[John Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover|John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury of Preston Candover''']] [[Knight of the Garter|K.G.]]<br>(b. 1927)|David=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[David Sainsbury, Baron Sainsbury of Turville|David John Sainsbury<br>'''Baron Sainsbury of Turville''']]<br>(b. 1940)|Michael=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Michael Havers, Baron Havers|Robert Michael Oldfield Havers<br>'''Baron Havers''']]<br>(1923\u20141992)|Elizabeth=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Ann Elizabeth Oldfield Butler-Sloss<br>'''Baroness Butler-Sloss''']]<br>(b. 1933)}}\n{{chart|!| | | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Sarah|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|~|Robert|Sarah=''The Honourable''<br>Sarah Jane Sainsbury<br>(b. 1964)|Robert=''The Honourable''<br>Robert Joseph Neville Galmoye Butler-Sloss<br>(b. 1962)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n\n===Hurd/Hurd of Westwell/Cowdrey of Tonbridge/Kerr of Monteviot===\nFour generations of the Hurd family have sat as Conservative MPs. The two middle generations have been given life peerages (Lord Hurd of Westwell notably serving as Foreign Secretary under Margaret Thatcher and John Major), and the youngest married the daughter of The Most Hon. the Marquess of '''Lothian''' and The Rt. Hon. the Lady '''Herries of Terregles''' in 2010. Lord Lothian also sat as a Conservative MP, and was given a life peerage upon retirement from the Commons. Despite already succeeding to his titles, he did so after the House of Lords Act 1999 removed the automatic right of hereditary peers to sit in the Lords, and so required a life peerage to be able to sit there. Lord Lothian married the 16th Lady Herries of Terregles in 1975. Her elder sister, the 14th Lady, married the cricketer Colin Cowdrey in 1985. Cowdrey was given a life peerage by outgoing Prime Minister John Major in 1997. The life peerages are\n* [[Anthony Hurd, Baron Hurd|Baron '''Hurd''', ''of Newbury in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1964)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43419/page/7261</ref>\n* [[Douglas Hurd|Baron '''Hurd of Westwell''', ''of Westwell in the county of Oxfordshire'']] (1997)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54810/page/7063</ref>\n* [[Colin Cowdrey|Baron '''Cowdrey of Tonbridge''', ''of Tonbridge in the county of Kent'']] (1997)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54842/page/8443</ref> and\n* [[Michael Ancram|Baron '''Kerr of Monteviot''', ''of Monteviot in Roxburghshire'']] (2010)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/L-59614-1254234</ref>\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Hurd, Hurd of Westwell, Cowdrey of Tonbridge and Kerr of Monteviot}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | |Norfolk| | | | | |Hurd|Norfolk=[[File:Coronet of a British Duke.svg|15px]]<br>[[Bernard Fitzalan-Howard, 16th Duke of Norfolk|Bernard Marmaduke Fitzalan-Howard<br>16th Duke of Norfolk]]<br>(1908\u20141975)|Hurd=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Anthony Hurd, Baron Hurd|Anthony Richard Hurd<br>'''Baron Hurd''']]<br>(1901\u20141966)}}\n{{chart| | | | | | |,|^|.| | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Cowdrey|~|14| |16|m|Kerr| |Hurd2|Cowdrey=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Colin Cowdrey|Michael Colin Cowdrey<br>'''Baron Cowdrey of Tonbridge''']]<br>(1932\u20142000)|14=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Anne Cowdrey, 14th Lady Herries of Terregles|Anne Elizabeth Cowdrey ''n\u00e9e Fitzalan-Howard''<br>14th Lady Herries of Terregles]]<br>(1938\u20142014)|16=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>Theresa Jane Kerr ''n\u00e9e Fitzalan-Howard''<br>16th Lady Herries of Terregles<br>(b. 1945)|Kerr=[[File:Coronet of a British Marquess.svg|15px]]<br>[[Michael Ancram|Michael Andrew Foster Jude Kerr<br>13th Marquess of Lothian<br>'''Baron Kerr of Monteviot''']]<br>(b. 1945)|Hurd2=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Douglas Hurd|Douglas Richard Hurd<br>'''Baron Hurd of Westwell''']]<br>(b. 1930)}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | |!|}}\n{{chart| | | | | | | | | | |LKerr|~|~|~|RHHurd|LKerr=''Lady''<br>Clare Therese Kerr<br>(b. 1979)|RHHurd=[[Nick Hurd|''Rt. Hon.''<br>Nicholas Richard Hurd]]<br>(b. 1962)}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n===The Brookes===\nBoth Barbara and her husband Henry Brooke were given life peerages, as was their son, Peter. The titles are:\n\n* [[Barbara Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte|Baroness '''Brooke of Ystradfellte''', ''of Ystradfellte in the County of Breconshire'']] (1964)\n* [[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor|Baron '''Brooke of Cumnor''', ''of Cumnor in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1966)\n* [[Peter Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville|Baron '''Brooke of Sutton Mandeville''', ''of Sutton Mandeville in the County of Wiltshire'']] (2001)\n\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Henry Brooke, Baron Brooke of Cumnor]] (1903\u20131984)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Barbara Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte|Barbara Muriel Brooke, Baroness Brooke of Ystradfellte]] ''n\u00e9e Mathews'' (1908\u20132000)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Peter Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville|Peter Leonard Brooke, Baron Brooke of Sutton Mandeville]] (b. 1934)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Spencer-Churchills and the Soames===\nClementine Churchill, wife of Prime Minister Winston Churchill, was created a life peer after her husband's death. One of their daughters married Christopher Soames in 1947, who was later ennobled in like manner. The titles are:\n\n* [[Clementine Churchill|Baroness '''Spencer-Churchill''', ''of Chartwell in the County of Kent'']] (1965)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/43654/supplement/4861</ref>\n* [[Christopher Soames|Baron '''Soames''', ''of Fletching in the County of East Sussex'']] (1978)\n\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]'' [[Clementine Churchill|Clementine Ogilvy Spencer-Churchill, Baroness Spencer-Churchill]] (1885\u20131977)''\n** ''[[Mary Soames|Mary Soames, Lady Soames]] ''n\u00e9e Spencer-Churchill'' (1922\u20132014)'' = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Christopher Soames|Arthur Christopher John Soames, Baron Soames]] (1920\u20131987)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Hoggs and Boyd-Carpenters===\nAside from the hereditary [[Viscount Hailsham|Barony and Viscountcy '''Hailsham''', ''of Hailsham in the County of Sussex'']] created for [[Douglas Hogg, 1st Viscount Hailsham|Douglas Hogg]], four members of these families have been given life peerages.\n[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin Hogg, 2nd Viscount Hailsham]] [[Peerage Act 1963|disclaimed]] his hereditary peerage in 1963, allowing him to take up a seat in the [[House of Commons]]. He was later given a life peerage in 1979 when he was appointed to the role of [[Lord Chancellor|Lord High Chancellor of Great Britain]]. His daughter-in-law was likewise ennobled for life as was her father. The 3rd Viscount was also given a life peerage, which enables him to sit in the House of Lords following the [[House of Lords Act 1999]], which automatically excludes most hereditary peers. The life peerages are\n* [[John Boyd-Carpenter, Baron Boyd-Carpenter|Baron '''Boyd-Carpenter''', ''of Crux Easton in the County of Southampton'']] (1972,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/45663/page/5315</ref> Conservative);\n* [[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Baron '''Hailsham of Saint Marylebone''', ''of Herstmonceux in the County of Sussex'']] (1979,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/18893/page/575</ref> Conservative);\n* [[Sarah Hogg, Viscountess Hailsham|Baroness '''Hogg''', ''of Kettlethorpe in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (1995,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/53948/page/1817</ref> ); and\n* [[Douglas Hogg|Baron '''Hailsham of Kettlethorpe''', ''of Kettlethorpe in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (2015,<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/2418750</ref>).\n{{chart top|width=100%|Family tree showing the relationships between Lords Hailsham of St Marylebone, Hailsham of Kettlethorpe, Boyd-Carpenter and Baroness Hogg}}\n{{chart/start|align=center}}\n{{chart|Quintin| |John|Quintin=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Quintin Hogg, Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone|Quintin McGarel Hogg<br>'''Baron Hailsham of St Marylebone''']]<br>''2nd Viscount Hailsham 1950\u20141963''<br>(1907\u20142001)|John=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[John Boyd-Carpenter, Baron Boyd-Carpenter|John Boyd-Carpenter<br>'''Baron Boyd-Carpenter''']]<br>(1908\u20141998))}}\n{{chart| |!| | | |!|}}\n{{chart|Douglas|~|Sarah|Douglas=[[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Douglas Hogg|Douglas Martin Hogg<br>3rd Viscount Hailsham<br>'''Baron Hailsham of Kettlethorpe''']]<br>(b. 1945)|Sarah=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]]<br>[[Sarah Hogg, Viscountess Hailsham|Sarah Elizabeth Mary Hogg ''n\u00e9e Boyd-Carpenter''<br>Viscountess Hailsham<br>'''Baroness Hogg''']]<br>(b. 1946)}}\n{{chart bottom}}\n{{chart/end}}\n===Rayne/Vane-Tempest-Stewart/Goldsmith===\nThe two daughters of the 8th Marquess of Londonderry connect two life peers; through marriage in one case through descent in the other. Lord Londonderry's elder daughter Lady Jane Vane-Tempest-Stewart married Sir Max Rayne in 1965. Lord Londonderry's younger daughter Lady Annabel Vane-Tempest-Stewart married Sir James Goldsmith (knighted in [[Harold Wilson|Harold Wilson's]] so-called [[1976 Prime Minister's Resignation Honours|'lavender list']]); one of their sons, Zac Goldsmith, was given a life peerage by Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] to enable him to stay on in the Cabinet after losing his [[Richmond Park (UK Parliament constituency)|Richmond Park seat]] in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 snap General Election]]. The titles are\n* [[Max Rayne|Baron '''Rayne''', ''of Prince's Meadow in Greater London'']] (1976)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46981/page/10687</ref>\n* [[Zac Goldsmith|Baron '''Goldsmith of Richmond Park''', ''of Richmond Park in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames'']] (2020)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/notice/3468585</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Marquess.svg|15px]] ''[[Robin Vane-Tempest-Stewart, 8th Marquess of Londonderry|Edward Charles Robert Vane-Tempest-Stewart, 8th Marquess of Londonderry]] (1902\u20141955)''\n** ''Lady'' Jane Antonia Frances Rayne, Lady Rayne ''n\u00e9e Vane-Tempest-Stewart'' (b. 1932) = [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Max Rayne|Max Rayne, Baron Rayne]] (1918\u20142003)''\n** [[Lady Annabel Goldsmith|''Lady'' Annabel Goldsmith ''n\u00e9e Vane-Tempest-Stewart'']] (b. 1934) = ''[[James Goldsmith|Sir James Michael Goldsmith]] (1933\u20141997)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Zac Goldsmith|Frank Zacharias Robin Goldsmith, Baron Goldsmith of Richmond Park]] (b. 1975)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Wolfsons/Rawlings===\nThe titles held by members of the Wolfson family are \n* [[Leonard Wolfson, Baron Wolfson|Baron '''Wolfson''', ''of Marylebone in the City of Westminster'']] (1985); \n* [[David Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Sunningdale|Baron '''Wolfson of Sunningdale''', ''of Trevose in the County of Cornwall'']] (1991);\n* [[Patricia Rawlings, Baroness Rawlings|Baroness '''Rawlings''', ''of Burnham Westgate in the County of Norfolk]] (1994); and\n* [[Simon Wolfson|Baron '''Wolfson of Aspley Guise''', ''of Aspley Guise in the County of Bedfordshire'']] (2010).\n{{tree list}}\n* ''Solomon Wolfson (1868 \u2013 1941)''\n** [[File:Ulster.svg|15px]] ''[[Isaac Wolfson|Sir Isaac Wolfson, 1st Bt]] (1897 \u2013 1991)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Leonard Wolfson, Baron Wolfson|Leonard Gordon Wolfson, Baron Wolfson]] (1927 \u2013 2010)''\n** ''Charles K. Wolfson (1899 \u2013 1970)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[David Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Sunningdale]] (b. 1935) ~ [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Patricia Rawlings, Baroness Rawlings]] (b. 1939)\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Simon Wolfson|Simon Adam Wolfson, Baron Wolfson of Aspley Guise]] (b. 1967)\n{{tree list/end}}\nLord Wolfson of Sunningdale and The Baroness Rawlings were married in 1962. Their marriage was dissolved in 1967.\n\n==Those related by blood==\n===The Watsons of Thankerton===\nBoth William Watson (1827\u20131899) and his third son, William Watson (1873\u20131948), were high ranking judges. Each were appointed Lord Advocate, and subsequently a Lord of Appeal in Ordinary. The titles are\n* [[William Watson, Baron Watson|Baron '''Watson''', ''of Thankerton, in the County of Lanark'']] (1880)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/24838/page/2725</ref> and\n* [[William Watson, Baron Thankerton|Baron '''Thankerton''' ''of Thankerton in the County of Lanark'']] (1929).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/Edinburgh/issue/14545/page/467</ref>\n\n===The Barons Russell of Killowen===\nThe title was created three times for father, son and grandson, all of them at some time Lords of Appeal in Ordinary. The titles are\n* [[Charles Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''', ''in the county of Down'']] (1894);<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/26511/page/2783</ref>\n* [[Frank Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''' ''of Killowen in the County of Down'']] (1929);<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/33553/page/7453</ref> and\n* [[Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Baron '''Russell of Killowen''', ''of Killowen in the County of Down'']] (1975).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46701/page/12332</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Charles Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Charles Arthur Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1832 \u2013 1900)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Frank Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Francis Xavier Joseph Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1867 \u2013 1946)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen|Charles Ritchie Russell, Baron Russell of Killowen]] (1908 \u2013 1986)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Youngers===\nAside from the hereditary [[Viscount Younger of Leckie|Viscountcy '''Younger of Leckie''', ''of Alloa in the County of Clackmannan'']] (1923), two members of the Younger family have been enobled for life. The younger brother of the first Viscount was a Law Lord and the 4th Viscount was given a peerage in the lifetime of his father, there being no possibility of a [[writ in acceleration]] as the Viscounts have no subsidiary barony. The life peerages are\n* [[Robert Younger, Baron Blanesburgh|Baron '''Blanesburgh''', ''of Alloa in the County of Clackmannanshire'']] (1923, Law Lord)\n* [[George Younger, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie|Baron '''Younger of Prestwick''', ''of Ayr in the District of Kyle and Carrick'']] (1992, Conservative)\n{{tree list}}\n* ''James Younger''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[George Younger, 1st Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1851\u20141929)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''James Younger, 2nd Viscount Younger of Leckie (1880\u20141946)''\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[Edward Younger, 3rd Viscount Younger of Leckie|Edward George Younger, 3rd Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1906\u20141997)''\n***** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]], [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] ''[[George Younger, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie|George Kenneth Hotson Younger, Baron Younger of Prestwick, 4th Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (1931\u20142003)''\n****** [[File:Coronet of a British Viscount.svg|15px]] [[James Younger, 5th Viscount Younger of Leckie|James Edward George Younger, 5th Viscount Younger of Leckie]] (b. 1955)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Robert Younger, Baron Blanesburgh]] (1861\u20141946)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n===The Keiths===\nBoth [[James Keith, Baron Keith of Avonholm|James Keith]] (1886\u20141964) and his only son, [[Henry Keith, Baron Keith of Kinkel|Henry Shanks Keith]] (1920\u20142002), were high-ranking judges. Both were [[Senator of the College of Justice|Senators of the College of Justice]] and subsequently [[Law Lord|Law Lords]], each taking the Scottish judicial title '''Lord Keith''' in 1937 and 1971 respectively, and then taking the following titles upon being made Law Lords:\n* [[James Keith, Baron Keith of Avonholm|Baron '''Keith of Avonholm''' ''of Saint Bernard's in the City of Edinburgh'']] (1953)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/40008/supplement/5921</ref> and\n* [[Henry Keith, Baron Keith of Kinkel|Baron '''Keith of Kinkel''', ''of Strathtummel in the District of Perth and Kinross'']] (1977).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/47120/page/471</ref>\n\n===Morrison and Mandleson===\nBoth notable [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politicians, Herbert Morrison and his grandson Peter Mandleson were given life peerages. Morrison held the position of [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Leader of the House of Commons]] under [[Clement Attlee|Clement Attlee, ''later'' 1st Earl Attlee]], as well as several other Cabinet positions. Mandleson was a key figure in the '[[New Labour]]' movement and a close confidant of 'New Labour' Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]], who appointed  him to several Cabinet positions, as well as to the position of [[European Commissioner for Trade#Mandelson (2004\u20132008)|European Commissioner for Trade]]. The titles are\n* [[Herbert Morrison|Baron '''Morrison of Lambeth''', ''of Lambeth in the County of London'']] (1959)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/41860/page/6942</ref> and\n* [[Peter Mandelson|Baron '''Mandleson''', ''of Foy in the County of Herefordshire and of Hartlepool in the County of Durham'']] (2008)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/58855/page/15991</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Herbert Morrison|''Herbert Stanley Morrison, Baron Morrison of Lambeth]] (1888\u20141965)''\n** ''Hon. Mary Joyce Mandleson ''n\u00e9e Morrison'' (1921\u20142006)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Peter Mandelson|Peter Benjamin Mandelson, Baron Mandelson]] (b. 1953)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===Bannerman and Michie===\nBoth John Bannerman and his daughter Ray Michie were ennobled for life. Their titles are\n* [[John Bannerman, Baron Bannerman of Kildonan|Baron '''Bannerman of Kildonan''', ''of Kildonan in the County of Sutherland'']] (1967, Scottish Liberal)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/44469/page/13287</ref>\n* [[Ray Michie|Baroness '''Michie of Gallanach''', ''of Oban in Argyll and Bute'']] (2001, Liberal Democrat).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/56281/page/8601</ref>\n\n===The Janners===\nBoth Barnett Janner (1892\u20141982) and his son, Greville Ewan Janner (1928\u20142015), served as Members of Parliament for [[Leicester West (UK Parliament constituency)|Leicester West]], Greville directly following his father. They were both subsequently ennobled with life peerages, which are\n* [[Barnett Janner, Baron Janner|Baron '''Janner''', ''of the City of Leicester'']] (1970, Labour)\n* [[Greville Janner|Baron '''Janner of Braunstone''', ''of Leicester in the County of Leicestershire'']] (1997, Labour).\n\n===The Frasers===\nIan Fraser was ennobled as a Law Lord in 1975. His son, a former Treasurer of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], was ennobled in [[David Cameron]]'s Resignation Honours List. The titles are\n* [[Ian Fraser, Baron Fraser of Tullybelton|Baron '''Fraser of Tullybelton''', ''of Bankfoot in the County of Perth'']] (1975, Law Lord), and\n* [[Andrew Fraser, Baron Fraser of Corriegarth|Baron '''Fraser of Corriegarth''', ''Corriegarth in the County of Inverness'']] (2016, Conservative).\n\n===Lindsay and Nicholson===\nJust under a year before succeeding to the Earldoms, Robert Lindsay (then styled ''Lord Balniel'') was given a life peerage. It is notable that he entered the House of Lords in this way, as he could conceivably have entered by [[writ in acceleration]] using one of his father's junior titles (such as the Wigan Barony, or even the Lindsay and Balniel Lordship of Parliament, with which was then styling himself). His third cousin was also ennobled for life. The titles are \n* [[Robert Lindsay, 29th Earl of Crawford|Baron '''Balniel''', ''of Pitcorthie in the County of Fife'']] (1975)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/46479/page/1231</ref> and\n* [[Emma Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne|Baroness '''Nicholson of Winterbourne''', ''of Winterbourne, in the Royal County of Berkshire'']] (1997).<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54942/page/12601</ref>\n{{tree list}}\n* [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[David Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford|David Alexander Edward Lindsay, 27th Earl of Crawford and 10th Earl of Balcarres]] (1871\u20131940)''\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] ''[[David Lindsay, 28th Earl of Crawford|David Alexander Robert Lindsay, 28th Earl of Crawford and 11th Earl of Balcarres]] (1900\u20131975)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]], [[File:Coronet of a British Earl.svg|15px]] [[Robert Lindsay, 29th Earl of Crawford|Robert Alexander Lindsay, Baron Balniel, ''subsequently'' 29th Earl of Crawford and 12th Earl of Balcarres]] (b. 1927)\n** ''Lady Katharine Constance Nicholson ''n\u00e9e Lindsay'' (1912\u20131972)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Emma Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne|Emma Harriet Nicholson, Baroness Nicholson of Winterbourne]] (b. 1941)\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===The Lane-Foxes===\nThe titles held by members of the Lane-Fox family are\n* [[Felicity Lane-Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox|Baroness '''Lane-Fox''', ''of Bramham in the County of West Yorkshire'']] (1981) and\n* [[Martha Lane Fox|Baroness '''Lane-Fox of Soho''', ''of Soho in the City of Westminster'']] (2013).\n{{tree list}}\n* ''Captain Edward Lane-Fox (1874\u20131949)''\n** James Henry Lane-Fox (b. 1912)\n*** [[Robin Lane Fox|Robin James Lane Fox]] (b. 1946)\n**** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Martha Lane Fox|Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]] (b. 1973)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Felicity Lane-Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox]] (1918\u20131988)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n===Callaghan and Jay===\nBoth former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom Jim Callaghan and his eldest daughter, Margaret Jay, were ennobled. Their titles are \n* [[James Callaghan|Baron '''Callaghan of Cardiff''', ''of the City of Cardiff in the County of South Glamorgan'']] (1987); and\n* [[Margaret Jay, Baroness Jay of Paddington|Baroness '''Jay of Paddington''', ''of Paddington in the City of Westminster'']] (1992).\n\n===The Palumbos===\nBoth Peter Palumbo and his eldest son, James, were ennobled. Their titles are \n* [[Peter Palumbo, Baron Palumbo|Baron '''Palumbo''', ''of Walbrook in the City of London'']] (1991); and\n* [[James Palumbo, Baron Palumbo of Southwark|Baron '''Palumbo of Southwark''', ''of Southwark, in the London Borough of Southwark'']] (2013).\n\n===The Morrises===\nAlf Morris, his brother Charles, and Charles's daughter Estelle were all Labour Members of Parliament. Alf and Estelle were both ennobled for life, their titles being\n* [[Alf Morris|Baron '''Morris of Manchester''', ''of Manchester, in the County of Greater Manchester'']] (1997, Labour)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/54915/page/11391</ref>; and\n* [[Estelle Morris|Baroness '''Morris of Yardley''', ''of Yardley, in the County of West Midlands'']] (2005, Labour)<ref>https://www.thegazette.co.uk/London/issue/57677/page/7919</ref> \n{{tree list}}\n* ''George Morris<ref>http://www.thepeerage.com/p63308.htm#i633078</ref>\n** ''[[Charles Morris (British politician)|Rt. Hon. Charles Richard Morris]] (1926\u20132012)''\n*** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] [[Estelle Morris|Estelle Morris, Baroness Morris of Yardley]] (b. 1952)\n** [[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|15px]] ''[[Alf Morris|Alfred Morris, Baron Morris of Manchester]] (1928\u20132012)''\n{{tree list/end}}\n\n==Those related by marriage==\n* [[Richard Llewelyn-Davies, Baron Llewelyn-Davies|Baron '''Llewelyn-Davies''', ''of Hastoe in the County of Hertfordshire'']] (1964) and\n* [[Annie Llewelyn-Davies, Baroness Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe|Baroness '''Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe''', ''of Hastoe in the County of Hertfordshire'']] (1967) married in 1943.\nAfter being widowed, Baroness Llewelyn-Davies of Hastoe developed a love affair at the end of her life with [[Cuthbert Alport|Baron '''Alport''', ''of Colchester in the County of Essex'']] (1961).\n\n\n* [[Edward Castle, Baron Castle|Baron '''Castle''', ''of Islington in Greater London'']] (1974) and\n* [[Barbara Castle|Baroness '''Castle of Blackburn''', ''of Ibstone in the County of Buckinghamshire'']] (1990) married in 1944.\n\n\n* [[Mary Stewart, Baroness Stewart of Alvechurch|Baroness '''Stewart of Alvechurch''', ''of Fulham in Greater London'']] (1975) and\n* [[Michael Stewart, Baron Stewart of Fulham|Baron '''Stewart of Fulham''', ''of Fulham in Greater London'']] (1979) married in 1941.\n\n\n* [[Sue Ryder|Baroness '''Ryder of Warsaw''', ''of Warsaw in Poland and of Cavendish in the County of Suffolk'']] (1979) and\n* [[Leonard Cheshire|Baron '''Cheshire''', ''of Woodhall in the County of Lincolnshire'']] (1991) married in 1959.\n\n\n* [[Hugh Griffiths, Baron Griffiths|Baron '''Griffiths''', ''of Govilon, in the County of Gwent'']] (1985) and\n* [[Heather Brigstocke, Baroness Brigstocke|Baroness '''Brigstocke''', ''of Kensington in the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea'']] (1990) married in 2000.\n\n\n* [[Geoffrey Howe|Baron '''Howe of Aberavon''', ''of Tandridge in the County of Surrey'']] (1992) and\n* [[Elspeth Howe, Baroness Howe of Idlicote|Baroness '''Howe of Idlicote''', ''of Shipston-on-Stour in the County of Warwickshire'']] (2001) married in 1953.\n\n\n* [[Diana Maddock, Baroness Maddock|Baroness '''Maddock''', ''of Christchurch in the County of Dorset'']] (1997) and \n* [[Alan Beith|Baron '''Beith''', ''of Berwick-upon-Tweed in the County of Northumberland'']] (2015) married in 2001.\n\n\n* [[Richard Layard, Baron Layard|Baron '''Layard''', ''of Highgate in the London Borough of Haringey'']] (2000) and \n* [[Molly Meacher, Baroness Meacher|Baroness '''Meacher''', ''of Spitalfields, in the London Borough of Tower Hamlets'']] (2006) married in 1991.\n\n\n* [[Robin Hodgson, Baron Hodgson of Astley Abbotts|Baron '''Hodgson of Astley Abbotts''', ''of Nash in the County of Shropshire'']] (2000)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55872 |date=12 June 2000 |page=6375}}</ref> and\n* [[Fiona Hodgson, Baroness Hodgson of Abinger|Baroness '''Hodgson of Abinger''', ''of Abinger in the County of Surrey'']] (2013)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=60632 |date=19 September 2013 |page=18509}}</ref> married in 1982.\n\n\n* [[Philip Gould, Baron Gould of Brookwood|Baron '''Gould of Brookwood''', ''of Brookwood in the County of Surrey'']] (2004) and\n* [[Gail Rebuck|Baroness '''Rebuck''', ''of Bloomsbury in the London Borough of Camden'']] (2014) were married from 1985 until Lord Gould of Brookwood's death in 2011.\n\n\n* [[Neil Kinnock|Baron '''Kinnock''', ''of Bedwellty in the County of Gwent'']] (2005) and\n* [[Glenys Kinnock, Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead|Baroness '''Kinnock of Holyhead''', ''of Holyhead in the County of Ynys M\u00f4n'']] (2009) married in 1967.\n\n\n*[[Eileen Paisley, Baroness Paisley of St George's|Baroness '''Paisley of St George's''', ''of St George's in the County of Antrim'']] (2006), one of the first three members of the [[Democratic Unionist Party|DUP]] to be made a life peer, and \n* [[Ian Paisley|Baron '''Bannside''', ''of North Antrim in the County of Antrim'']] (2010), one of the founders of the party, married in 1956.\n\n==See also==\nThe title [[Irene Curzon, 2nd Baroness Ravensdale|Baroness '''Ravensdale of Kedleston''', ''of Kedleston, in the County of Derby'']] (1958) was given to Irene Curzon, 2nd [[Baron Ravensdale|Baroness '''Ravensdale''', ''of Ravensdale in the County of Derby'']] (1911) to enable her to take a seat in the House of Lords as it was only after the [[Peerage Act 1963]] that ''suo jure'' peeresses could sit in the House by virtue of their hereditary peerages. She was the eldest daughter of [[George Curzon, 1st Marquess Curzon of Kedleston|The Marquess Curzon of Kedleston]], and therefore related to not only future Barons Ravensdale, but also the Barons and [[Viscount Scarsdale|Viscounts Scarsdale]].\n\n[[Evelyn Emmet, Baroness Emmet of Amberley|Baroness '''Emmet of Amberley''', ''of Amberley in the County of Sussex'']] (1965), was the eldest daughter of [[Rennell Rodd, 1st Baron Rennell]].\n\n[[George Howard, Baron Howard of Henderskelfe|Baron '''Howard of Henderskelfe''', ''of Henderskelfe in the County of North Yorkshire'']] (1983), who was in line to succeed to the [[Earl of Carlisle|Earldom of Carlisle]].\n\n[[Hugh Cavendish, Baron Cavendish of Furness|Baron '''Cavendish of Furness''', ''of Cartmel in the County of Cumbria'']] (1990), who is in the line of succession to the [[Duke of Devonshire|Dukedom of Devonshire]].\n\n[[Greville Howard, Baron Howard of Rising|Baron '''Howard of Rising''', ''of Castle Rising in the County of Norfolk'']] (2004), who is in the line of succession to the [[Earl of Suffolk|Earldoms of Suffolk and Berkshire]].\n\n[[Eliza Manningham-Buller|Baroness '''Manningham-Buller''', ''of Northampton in the County of Northamptonshire'']] (2008), who is the second daughter of [[Reginald Manningham-Buller, 1st Viscount Dilhorne]]. The [[Viscount Dilhorne|Dilhorne Viscountcy]] is the most recently-created extant one.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Related Life Peers}}\n[[Category:Life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lists of British nobility]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: recently- \u2192 recently , enobled \u2192 ennobled", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_related_life_peers"}
{"title_page": "Olympic Truce", "text_new": "The '''Olympic Truce''' is a tradition originating from [[Ancient Greece]] that dates back to 776 BC. A \"[[truce]]\" (Ancient Greek: [[Ekecheiria|\u00e9k\u00e9cheiria]], meaning \"laying down of arms\") was announced before and during the [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic Games]] to ensure the host city-state ([[Elis]]) was not attacked and athletes and spectators could travel safely to the Games and peacefully return to their respective countries.\n\nIn 1992, the [[International Olympic Committee]] renewed this tradition by calling upon all nations to observe the Truce during the [[Olympic Games|modern Games]]. The Truce was revived by [[United Nations]] Resolution 48/11 of 25 October 1993,<ref>https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/</ref> as well by the [[United Nations Millennium Declaration]] relating to the world peace and security.<ref>[[United Nations Millennium Declaration]], Article 10</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the Athens Bid Committee committed to reviving the Olympic Truce and promoting it to the world through the [[Olympic flame]] relay.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olympic Truce Centre|title=Olympic Truce Milestones|url=http://www.olympictruce.org/discover/timeline.php|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> Three years later, the International Olympic Committee announced the establishment of the '''International Olympic Truce Foundation''' and the International Olympic Truce Centre in cooperation with Greece.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.olympictruce.org/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=3&Itemid=268&lang=en | title=The Truce timeline | publisher=International Olympic Truce Center | accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref> The vision was to protect the interests of athletes and sport and to promote peaceful principles in modern-day. Each host city was encouraged to embrace the meaning and spirit of the Olympic Truce in the planning and staging of the Games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Olympic  Truce|url=http://www.olympic.org/content/the-ioc/commissions/international-relations-/olympic-truce/?tab=initiatives-for-peace|website=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n== Goals ==\nThrough this global and symbolic concept, the goal of the Olympic Truce movement is to:{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n* Mobilize youth for the promotion of the Olympic ideals\n* Use sport to establish contacts between communities in conflict\n* Offer humanitarian support in countries at war\n* Create a window of opportunities for dialogue and reconciliation\n\n== Initiatives ==\n* [[1994 Winter Olympics|1994 Lillehammer Winter Games]]: the former Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was allowed to participate in the Games of the XXV Olympiad in Barcelona and the XVII Olympic Winter Games in Lillehammer despite ongoing wars. A delegation from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) visited Sarajevo in 1994 to extend its solidarity to the city that had organized the XIV Olympic Winter Games in 1984.\n* [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998 Nagano Winter Games]]: During a time when tension in the Persian Gulf region was high, United Nations Secretary General [[Kofi Annan]] intervened to seek a diplomatic resolution to the crisis in Iraq. In a release from the International Olympic Committee, the Secretary General was quoted, ''I call upon all nations to observe the Olympic truce.''<ref>{{cite news|last=Longman|first=Jere|title=OLYMPICS: NAGANO 1998; I.O.C. Asks White House To Honor Peace Pledge|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/04/sports/olympics-nagano-1998-ioc-asks-white-house-to-honor-peace-pledge.html|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=February 4, 1998}}</ref>\n* [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Summer Games]]: During the Opening Ceremony, South and North Korean delegations walked in the stadium together, under the same flag. It was the first Olympic Games event where the two divided countries walked side by side.<ref>{{cite news|title=Koreas to March Into Olympics Together|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/story?id=100609&page=1|accessdate=July 22, 2011|newspaper=ABC News|date=September 10, 2000}}</ref>\n* [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens Summer Games]]: The Olympic Truce was promoted through Olympic Flame Relay events. The UN supported the IOC in asking the nations of the world to stop all wars for 16 days during the Games.\n* [[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin Winter Games]]: During the games, athletes and officials showed support for the Olympic Truce by signing one of the three walls situated in the three Olympic Villages (Turin, Sestriere and Bardonecchia).\n* [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver Winter Games]]: Truce projects were rooted in an open invitation for people to 'Make Your Peace' which asked individuals to create everyday peace at home, schools, work, and in the community. Projects included: delivering Olympic Spirit Boxes filled with hockey, soccer, lacrosse, baseball, and basketball equipment to 20 Aboriginal communities in Northern Canada;<ref>{{cite news|last=Canada National Defense|title=Olympic Truce initiative takes to the skies|url=http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/17w-17e/nr-sp/index-eng.asp?id=9934|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=January 5, 2010}}</ref> an Olympic Truce Youth Dialogue with Canada's Governor General;<ref>{{cite news|last=Governor General of Canada|author-link=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General to Host Youth Dialogue  in Celebration of the Vancouver 2010 Olympic Winter Games|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=13508|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=February 4, 2011}}</ref> and an art installation titled \"Room to Make your Peace\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Vancouver Olympic Games|title=Room to Make Your Peace: 2010|url=http://72.35.10.20/paralympic-games/more-2010-information/cultural-festivals-and-events/code-connect-create-collaborate/code-live/code-live-3/|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 London Summer Games ===\n\nOn 22 April 2011 a Member of the House of Lords - [[Michael Bates, Baron Bates]] - began walking over 3000 miles from Olympia to London to highlight the opportunity to bring the Olympic Truce into reality during the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Summer Games]]. [http://www.walkfortruce.org/ Walk for Truce], Lord Bates was successful in securing pledges from a number of governments to both sign and implement the Truce, supported on his journey by the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|British Foreign Office]]. Lord Bates arrived back in London on February 15, 2012 and continues to lobby for the cause of the Olympic Truce.\n\nThe UK promoted the ideals of the Olympic Truce both domestically, and for the first time internationally.  The London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) organised truce activities in the UK including: \"Get Set for the Olympic Truce\" which encourages young people across the UK to learn about the history of the Olympic Truce, to debate and discuss what the Olympic Truce means to their lives and to undertake an activity to promote peace within their school or community. Materials were promoted to over 20,000 schools registered with Get Set.\n\nTruce Inspire is a \u2018truce\u2019 strand of the Inspire programme through which LOCOG specifically looked for projects inspired by the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games which use sport or culture to promote conflict resolution, reconciliation and peace. LOCOG approved a number of projects including: a project led by the University of Ulster which uses sport to support conflict resolution across the education sector; a project providing 200 schools with the opportunity to debate the theme of the Olympic Truce at a Model UN conference; and a project which uses sport to bring together young people from London communities affected by gang rivalry. Cultural Olympiad and the London 2012 Festival organised by LOCOG and the NGO Peace One Day is delivering a truce strand of the Film Nation Shorts project through which 14- to 25-year-olds are invited to create films focused on the truce theme. LOCOG has also partnered with Peace One Day to deliver a series of concerts as part of the London 2012 Festival.\n\nInternational activities were led by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) which together with [http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/global-issues/london-2012/olympic-truce/ partners promoted the ideals of the Olympic Truce internationally] under the themes of:\n\n* \"Local solutions to local problems: Preventing conflict and building peace requires the involvement of the local communities who are most affected. We are looking for opportunities to work with host governments, communities, faith groups, civil society and the media to build relationships across boundaries.\n* Legitimate Politics: Legitimate politics are essential for peace. The most peaceful political systems are accountable, give everybody a voice and are trusted to manage difference and accommodate change. We are seeking to work with Parliamentarians and bodies such as the Inter-Parliamentary Union, the Westminster Foundation for Democracy and Commonwealth to promote the Truce and encourage public commitments to conflict prevention and peace-building.\n* Building a 2012 Truce legacy: Through an active public diplomacy programme we have an opportunity to increase international public interest and involvement in conflict prevention and peace-building and to raise the level of ambition for future Olympic Truces\".\n\nSpeaking about the FCO's work on the Olympic Truce, Foreign Office Minister Henry Bellingham said\n{{Quote|As the Minister with responsibility for Conflict Issues, I am delighted to introduce the FCO's Olympic Truce activities. Our staff in the UK and Missions across the world will undertake activities and events to promote the ideals of peace and conflict resolution ahead of the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games. We want to make the most of this historic opportunity and work with other governments, the United Nations, the International Olympic Committee, National Olympic Committees, the International Paralympic Committee, National Paralympic Committees, NGOs and civil society to promote the principles and ideals of the Olympic Truce.}}\n\nOn 28 May 2012 during the visit of Foreign Secretary William Hague to Moscow, the UK and Russian foreign ministries (in recognistion of their countries shared roles as Olympic Hosts in 2012 and 2014) agreed to [http://uk.sitestat.com/fcoweb/ukingov/s?nd.rus.en.about-us.working-with-russia.012-visits.hague-2011.p.pdf.olympic-truce-eng&ns_type=pdf&ns_url=http://ukinrussia.fco.gov.uk/resources/en/pdf/21121586/661004282/olympic-truce-eng work together] to promote and support the ideals of the Olympic Truce.\n\nOn 12 September 2012 FCO Ministers updated Parliament<ref>https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/wmstext/120912m0001.htm</ref>\n\"It was a real honour for the UK to have the responsibility to promote the Olympic truce message. We worked closely on delivering an international response to the Olympic truce, working with the London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic games, the Department for International Development, the Ministry of Defence and the Department for Culture Media and Sport\".\n\n\"We wanted to show that the UN resolution could be translated into international action. Our diplomatic missions across our network and the FCO in London arranged over 70 events and activities which showed how important the contribution of youth, women and those with disabilities is in promoting peace through sport, culture, education and wider public engagement. While activities took place in every continent, we specifically wanted to bring the Olympic truce to life in conflict affected and fragile countries\".\n\n\"The UK is the first games host to deliver this level of international ambition for the Olympic truce. The UN Secretary-General, in the presence of the International Olympic Committee, recognised the UK\u2019s Olympic truce work on the eve of the opening ceremony of the London 2012 games. Now others are seeking to build on our experience. We are currently sharing our experience with the UN Secretary-General\u2019s Special Adviser\u2019s Office on sport and development for peace, as well as with Russia, which will next take stewardship of the Olympic truce in 2013, ahead of the Sochi winter games in 2014. This level of international interest, paired with our continued engagement, will help cement our legacy of encouraging future games hosts to promote the ideals of the Olympic truce in their own ways\".\n\n== Logo ==\nThe official [http://www.olympictruce.org/images/LOGO_TRANS.png Olympic Truce logo] is a graphic with three elements: a dove, flames, and the Olympic rings. The meaning behind the logo is as follows:\n:The Olympic Truce is symbolized by the dove of peace with the traditional Olympic flame in the background. In a world that is plagued by wars and animosity, the peace-dove symbol represents one of the IOC's ideals to build a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal. The Olympic flame has brought warm friendship to all the people of the world through sharing and global togetherness. In the symbol, the flame is made up of colourful effervescent elements, reminiscent of festivities experienced in the celebration of the human spirit. These elements represent people of all races coming together for the observance of the Truce.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olympic.org|title=Olympic Truce|url=http://www.olympic.org/content/the-ioc/commissions/international-relations-/olympic-truce/|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==United Nations support==\n{{Quote|text=Today the Olympic Truce has become an expression of mankind's desire to build a world based on the rules of fair competition, peace, humanity and reconciliation.|sign=|source=https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/background.shtml}}\nThe United Nations is in support of the Olympic Truce and before each Summer and Winter Olympic Games, adopts a resolution called \"Building a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=a/66/l.3 |title=Building a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 October 2011 |website= |publisher=United Nations General Assembly |access-date=October 10, 2015 |quote=}}</ref> UN Member States are asked to observe the Olympic Truce, and work towards the settlement of international disagreements by peaceful and diplomatic means.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roukhadze|first=Marie-H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|title=The Olympic Winter Games: Fundamentals and Ceremonies|url=http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_267.pdf|publisher=IOC|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> The [[United Kingdom]] was the first ever nation to get all 193 UN Member states to [https://www.un.org/wcm/webdav/site/sport/shared/sport/pdfs/Resolutions/A-RES-66-5/A-RES-66-5_EN.pdf sign the Olympic Truce] resolution for the [[2012 Olympic Games]].\n\nUN Support is mainly shown through the resolution.  It is also shown by the Solemn Appeals for Truce made by the UN Secretary General and the President of the General Assembly shortly before the Olympic and Winter Olympic Games. The lead office within the UN system is The United Nations Office on Sport for Development and Peace or UNOSDP. The current UN Special Adviser on Sport for Development and Peace is Wilfried Lemke from Bremen, Germany. UNOSDP is situated at the UN Office at Geneva plus a liaison office at UN HQ in New York.\n\nOn 17 October 2011, the international community pledged to observe the Olympic Truce, individually and collectively.<ref>https://www.un.org/wcm/webdav/site/sport/shared/sport/pdfs/Resolutions/A-RES-66-5/A-RES-66-5_EN.pdf</ref>  For London 2012, the resolution was officially titled \u201cSport for Peace and Development: Building a Peaceful and Better World through Sport and the Olympic Ideal\u201d and was introduced by LOCOG chairman Sebastian Coe. \u201cThe Truce helps to show the world that peace is a possibility,\" he said Monday in New York City. \"It shows the power that sport has to inspire unity, mutual understanding, and respect among different types of people.\u201d Coe exhorted all member states of the UN to respect the ideals of the Truce. \u201cCountries should feel an obligation to respect the Truce because it holds true to the idea that we can coexist without the need for discrimination and fighting,\" he urged. \u201cIt gives us something to strive towards outside of the Olympics and the arena of sport.\u201d<ref>[http://aroundtherings.com/articles/view.aspx?id=38214 On the Scene -- UN Adopts Olympic Truce] \u2013 Around the Rings website</ref>\n\nThe United Nations website recognizes the truce as \"the cornerstone of the Olympic Games in ancient times\" and the \"longest lasting peace accord in history\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/background.shtml|title=United Nations and the Olympic Truce|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-05-29}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ancient Olympic Games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/ United Nations]\n* [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/Olympics/truce.html Perseus Digital Library]\n\n[[Category:History of the Olympics]]\n[[Category:Ceasefires]]\n\nthanks for reading i hope this helped :))\n", "text_old": "The '''Olympic Truce''' is a tradition originating from [[Ancient Greece]] that dates back to 776 BC. A \"[[truce]]\" (Ancient Greek: [[Ekecheiria|\u00e9k\u00e9cheiria]], meaning \"laying down of arms\") was announced before and during the [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic Games]] to ensure the host city state ([[Elis]]) was not attacked and athletes and spectators could travel safely to the Games and peacefully return to their respective countries.\n\nIn 1992, the [[International Olympic Committee]] renewed this tradition by calling upon all nations to observe the Truce during the [[Olympic Games|modern Games]]. The Truce was revived by [[United Nations]] Resolution 48/11 of 25 October 1993,<ref>https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/</ref> as well by the [[United Nations Millennium Declaration]] relating to the world peace and security.<ref>[[United Nations Millennium Declaration]], Article 10</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the Athens Bid Committee committed to reviving the Olympic Truce and promoting it to the world through the [[Olympic flame]] relay.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olympic Truce Centre|title=Olympic Truce Milestones|url=http://www.olympictruce.org/discover/timeline.php|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> Three years later, the International Olympic Committee announced the establishment of the '''International Olympic Truce Foundation''' and the International Olympic Truce Centre in cooperation with Greece.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.olympictruce.org/index.php?option=com_k2&view=item&layout=item&id=3&Itemid=268&lang=en | title=The Truce timeline | publisher=International Olympic Truce Center | accessdate=September 7, 2017}}</ref> The vision was to protect the interests of athletes and sport, and to promote peaceful principles in modern day. Each host city was encouraged to embrace the meaning and spirit of the Olympic Truce in the planning and staging of the Games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Olympic  Truce|url=http://www.olympic.org/content/the-ioc/commissions/international-relations-/olympic-truce/?tab=initiatives-for-peace|website=International Olympic Committee|accessdate=April 2, 2015}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n== Goals ==\nThrough this global and symbolic concept, the goal of the Olympic Truce movement is to:{{citation needed|date=August 2011}}\n\n* Mobilize youth for the promotion of the Olympic ideals\n* Use sport to establish contacts between communities in conflict\n* Offer humanitarian support in countries at war\n* Create a window of opportunities for dialogue and reconciliation\n\n== Initiatives ==\n* [[1994 Winter Olympics|1994 Lillehammer Winter Games]]: the former Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was allowed to participate in the Games of the XXV Olympiad in Barcelona and the XVII Olympic Winter Games in Lillehammer despite ongoing wars. A delegation from the International Olympic Committee (IOC) visited Sarajevo in 1994 to extend its solidarity to the city that had organized the XIV Olympic Winter Games in 1984.\n* [[1998 Winter Olympics|1998 Nagano Winter Games]]: During a time when tension in the Persian Gulf region was high, United Nations Secretary General [[Kofi Annan]] intervened to seek a diplomatic resolution to the crisis in Iraq. In a release from the International Olympic Committee, the Secretary General was quoted, ''I call upon all nations to observe the Olympic truce.''<ref>{{cite news|last=Longman|first=Jere|title=OLYMPICS: NAGANO 1998; I.O.C. Asks White House To Honor Peace Pledge|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/04/sports/olympics-nagano-1998-ioc-asks-white-house-to-honor-peace-pledge.html|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=February 4, 1998}}</ref>\n* [[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney Summer Games]]: During the Opening Ceremony, South and North Korean delegations walked in the stadium together, under the same flag. It was the first Olympic Games event where the two divided countries walked side by side.<ref>{{cite news|title=Koreas to March Into Olympics Together|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/story?id=100609&page=1|accessdate=July 22, 2011|newspaper=ABC News|date=September 10, 2000}}</ref>\n* [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Athens Summer Games]]: The Olympic Truce was promoted through Olympic Flame Relay events. The UN supported the IOC in asking the nations of the world to stop all wars for 16 days during the Games.\n* [[2006 Winter Olympics|2006 Turin Winter Games]]: During the games, athletes and officials showed support for the Olympic Truce by signing one of the three walls situated in the three Olympic Villages (Turin, Sestriere and Bardonecchia).\n* [[2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver Winter Games]]: Truce projects were rooted in an open invitation for people to 'Make Your Peace' which asked individuals to create everyday peace at home, schools, work, and in the community. Projects included: delivering Olympic Spirit Boxes filled with hockey, soccer, lacrosse, baseball, and basketball equipment to 20 Aboriginal communities in Northern Canada;<ref>{{cite news|last=Canada National Defense|title=Olympic Truce initiative takes to the skies|url=http://www.airforce.forces.gc.ca/17w-17e/nr-sp/index-eng.asp?id=9934|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=January 5, 2010}}</ref> an Olympic Truce Youth Dialogue with Canada's Governor General;<ref>{{cite news|last=Governor General of Canada|author-link=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General to Host Youth Dialogue  in Celebration of the Vancouver 2010 Olympic Winter Games|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=13508|accessdate=July 22, 2011|date=February 4, 2011}}</ref> and an art installation titled \"Room to Make your Peace\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Vancouver Olympic Games|title=Room to Make Your Peace: 2010|url=http://72.35.10.20/paralympic-games/more-2010-information/cultural-festivals-and-events/code-connect-create-collaborate/code-live/code-live-3/|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== 2012 London Summer Games ===\n\nOn 22 April 2011 a Member of the House of Lords - [[Michael Bates, Baron Bates]] - began walking over 3000 miles from Olympia to London to highlight the opportunity to bring the Olympic Truce into reality during the [[2012 Summer Olympics|2012 London Summer Games]]. [http://www.walkfortruce.org/ Walk for Truce], Lord Bates was successful in securing pledges from a number of governments to both sign and implement the Truce, supported on his journey by the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office|British Foreign Office]]. Lord Bates arrived back in London on February 15, 2012 and continues to lobby for the cause of the Olympic Truce.\n\nThe UK promoted the ideals of the Olympic Truce both domestically, and for the first time internationally.  The London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games (LOCOG) organised truce activities in the UK including: \"Get Set for the Olympic Truce\" which encourages young people across the UK to learn about the history of the Olympic Truce, to debate and discuss what the Olympic Truce means to their lives and to undertake an activity to promote peace within their school or community. Materials were promoted to over 20,000 schools registered with Get Set.\n\nTruce Inspire is a \u2018truce\u2019 strand of the Inspire programme through which LOCOG specifically looked for projects inspired by the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games which use sport or culture to promote conflict resolution, reconciliation and peace. LOCOG approved a number of projects including: a project led by the University of Ulster which uses sport to support conflict resolution across the education sector; a project providing 200 schools with the opportunity to debate the theme of the Olympic Truce at a Model UN conference; and a project which uses sport to bring together young people from London communities affected by gang rivalry. Cultural Olympiad and the London 2012 Festival organised by LOCOG and the NGO Peace One Day is delivering a truce strand of the Film Nation Shorts project through which 14- to 25-year-olds are invited to create films focused on the truce theme. LOCOG has also partnered with Peace One Day to deliver a series of concerts as part of the London 2012 Festival.\n\nInternational activities were led by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) which together with [http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/global-issues/london-2012/olympic-truce/ partners promoted the ideals of the Olympic Truce internationally] under the themes of:\n\n* \"Local solutions to local problems: Preventing conflict and building peace requires the involvement of the local communities who are most affected. We are looking for opportunities to work with host governments, communities, faith groups, civil society and the media to build relationships across boundaries.\n* Legitimate Politics: Legitimate politics are essential for peace. The most peaceful political systems are accountable, give everybody a voice and are trusted to manage difference and accommodate change. We are seeking to work with Parliamentarians and bodies such as the Inter-Parliamentary Union, the Westminster Foundation for Democracy and Commonwealth to promote the Truce and encourage public commitments to conflict prevention and peace-building.\n* Building a 2012 Truce legacy: Through an active public diplomacy programme we have an opportunity to increase international public interest and involvement in conflict prevention and peace-building and to raise the level of ambition for future Olympic Truces\".\n\nSpeaking about the FCO's work on the Olympic Truce, Foreign Office Minister Henry Bellingham said\n{{Quote|As the Minister with responsibility for Conflict Issues, I am delighted to introduce the FCO's Olympic Truce activities. Our staff in the UK and Missions across the world will undertake activities and events to promote the ideals of peace and conflict resolution ahead of the London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games. We want to make the most of this historic opportunity and work with other governments, the United Nations, the International Olympic Committee, National Olympic Committees, the International Paralympic Committee, National Paralympic Committees, NGOs and civil society to promote the principles and ideals of the Olympic Truce.}}\n\nOn 28 May 2012 during the visit of Foreign Secretary William Hague to Moscow, the UK and Russian foreign ministries (in recognistion of their countries shared roles as Olympic Hosts in 2012 and 2014) agreed to [http://uk.sitestat.com/fcoweb/ukingov/s?nd.rus.en.about-us.working-with-russia.012-visits.hague-2011.p.pdf.olympic-truce-eng&ns_type=pdf&ns_url=http://ukinrussia.fco.gov.uk/resources/en/pdf/21121586/661004282/olympic-truce-eng work together] to promote and support the ideals of the Olympic Truce.\n\nOn 12 September 2012 FCO Ministers updated Parliament<ref>https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm120912/wmstext/120912m0001.htm</ref>\n\"It was a real honour for the UK to have the responsibility to promote the Olympic truce message. We worked closely on delivering an international response to the Olympic truce, working with the London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic games, the Department for International Development, the Ministry of Defence and the Department for Culture Media and Sport\".\n\n\"We wanted to show that the UN resolution could be translated into international action. Our diplomatic missions across our network and the FCO in London arranged over 70 events and activities which showed how important the contribution of youth, women and those with disabilities is in promoting peace through sport, culture, education and wider public engagement. While activities took place in every continent, we specifically wanted to bring the Olympic truce to life in conflict affected and fragile countries\".\n\n\"The UK is the first games host to deliver this level of international ambition for the Olympic truce. The UN Secretary-General, in the presence of the International Olympic Committee, recognised the UK\u2019s Olympic truce work on the eve of the opening ceremony of the London 2012 games. Now others are seeking to build on our experience. We are currently sharing our experience with the UN Secretary-General\u2019s Special Adviser\u2019s Office on sport and development for peace, as well as with Russia, which will next take stewardship of the Olympic truce in 2013, ahead of the Sochi winter games in 2014. This level of international interest, paired with our continued engagement, will help cement our legacy of encouraging future games hosts to promote the ideals of the Olympic truce in their own ways\".\n\n== Logo ==\nThe official [http://www.olympictruce.org/images/LOGO_TRANS.png Olympic Truce logo] is a graphic with three elements: a dove, flames, and the Olympic rings. The meaning behind the logo is as follows:\n:The Olympic Truce is symbolized by the dove of peace with the traditional Olympic flame in the background. In a world that is plagued by wars and animosity, the peace-dove symbol represents one of the IOC's ideals to build a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal. The Olympic flame has brought warm friendship to all the people of the world through sharing and global togetherness. In the symbol, the flame is made up of colourful effervescent elements, reminiscent of festivities experienced in the celebration of the human spirit. These elements represent people of all races coming together for the observance of the Truce.<ref>{{cite web|last=Olympic.org|title=Olympic Truce|url=http://www.olympic.org/content/the-ioc/commissions/international-relations-/olympic-truce/|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==United Nations support==\n{{Quote|text=Today the Olympic Truce has become an expression of mankind's desire to build a world based on the rules of fair competition, peace, humanity and reconciliation.|sign=|source=https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/background.shtml}}\nThe United Nations is in support of the Olympic Truce and before each Summer and Winter Olympic Games, adopts a resolution called \"Building a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/ga/search/view_doc.asp?symbol=a/66/l.3 |title=Building a peaceful and better world through sport and the Olympic ideal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=11 October 2011 |website= |publisher=United Nations General Assembly |access-date=October 10, 2015 |quote=}}</ref> UN Member States are asked to observe the Olympic Truce, and work towards the settlement of international disagreements by peaceful and diplomatic means.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roukhadze|first=Marie-H\u00e9l\u00e8ne|title=The Olympic Winter Games: Fundamentals and Ceremonies|url=http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Reports/EN/en_report_267.pdf|publisher=IOC|accessdate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> The [[United Kingdom]] was the first ever nation to get all 193 UN Member states to [https://www.un.org/wcm/webdav/site/sport/shared/sport/pdfs/Resolutions/A-RES-66-5/A-RES-66-5_EN.pdf sign the Olympic Truce] resolution for the [[2012 Olympic Games]].\n\nUN Support is mainly shown through the resolution.  It is also shown by the Solemn Appeals for Truce made by the UN Secretary General and the President of the General Assembly shortly before the Olympic and Winter Olympic Games. The lead office within the UN system is The United Nations Office on Sport for Development and Peace or UNOSDP. The current UN Special Adviser on Sport for Development and Peace is Wilfried Lemke from Bremen, Germany. UNOSDP is situated at the UN Office at Geneva plus a liaison office at UN HQ in New York.\n\nOn 17 October 2011, the international community pledged to observe the Olympic Truce, individually and collectively.<ref>https://www.un.org/wcm/webdav/site/sport/shared/sport/pdfs/Resolutions/A-RES-66-5/A-RES-66-5_EN.pdf</ref>  For London 2012, the resolution was officially titled \u201cSport for Peace and Development: Building a Peaceful and Better World through Sport and the Olympic Ideal\u201d and was introduced by LOCOG chairman Sebastian Coe. \u201cThe Truce helps to show the world that peace is a possibility,\" he said Monday in New York City. \"It shows the power that sport has to inspire unity, mutual understanding, and respect among different types of people.\u201d Coe exhorted all member states of the UN to respect the ideals of the Truce. \u201cCountries should feel an obligation to respect the Truce because it holds true to the idea that we can coexist without the need for discrimination and fighting,\" he urged. \u201cIt gives us something to strive towards outside of the Olympics and the arena of sport.\u201d<ref>[http://aroundtherings.com/articles/view.aspx?id=38214 On the Scene -- UN Adopts Olympic Truce] \u2013 Around the Rings website</ref>\n\nThe United Nations website recognizes the truce as \"the cornerstone of the Olympic Games in ancient times\" and the \"longest lasting peace accord in history\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/background.shtml|title=United Nations and the Olympic Truce|website=www.un.org|language=EN|access-date=2016-05-29}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ancient Olympic Games]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.un.org/events/olympictruce/ United Nations]\n* [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/Olympics/truce.html Perseus Digital Library]\n\n[[Category:History of the Olympics]]\n[[Category:Ceasefires]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:a800:4f00:d571:8b01:99bd:f39a", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olympic_Truce"}
{"title_page": "John Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud", "text_new": "{{short description|British civil servant and diplomat}}\n{{redirect|John Maud|the bishop|John Maud (bishop)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n__NOTOC__\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Redcliffe-Maud\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCB|CBE}}\n|image            = File:John Redcliffe-Maud.jpg\n|imagesize        = 180px\n|smallimage       = \n|caption          = Portrait of John Redcliffe-Maud.\n|birthname        = John Primatt Redcliffe Maud<!-- Unhyphenated at birth -->\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1906|2|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Bristol]], England\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1982|11|20|1906|2|3|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Oxford]], England\n|restingplace     = [[Holywell Cemetery]], [[Oxford]], England\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|nationality      = British\n|party            =\n|occupation       = civil servant\n}}\n\n'''John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|CBE}} (3 February 1906 \u2013 20 November 1982) was a British civil servant and diplomat.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=3814&inst_id=1 | title=Maud, John Primatt Redcliffe Redcliffe-, 1906\u20131982, Baron Redcliffe-Maud of Bristol, civil servant and diplomat | website=[[AIM25]] | location=UK | accessdate=19 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/31427| title = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| year = 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Bristol]], Maud was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[New College, Oxford]]. He gained a Second in Classical Moderations in 1928 and a First in Literae Humaniores ('Greats') in 1928.<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1932'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1932, pp. 263, 312</ref> At [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] he was a member of the [[Oxford University Dramatic Society]] (OUDS). In 1928, he gained the one-year Henry P. Davison scholarship to [[Harvard University]]<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1932'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1932, p.344</ref> where he was awarded an A.B. in 1929.<ref name=\"Who's Who 1965\">''Who's Who, 1965'', London : A. & C. Black, 1965, p.2063</ref> From 1929 to 1932 he was a Junior Research Fellow [[University College, Oxford]] and from 1932-39 Fellow (Praelector in Politics)<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1935'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1935, p.274</ref> and Dean of the college. He was awarded a Rhodes Travelling Scholarship to Africa in 1932 and held a University Lectureship in Politics at Oxford University, 1938\u20139.<ref name=\"Who's Who 1965\"/>\n\n==Civil service==\nDuring [[World War II]], he was [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck College]] (1939\u20131943)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/about-us/past-officers |title=Prinicipals and Masters |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Birkbeck University of London |publisher= |access-date=3 October 2019 |quote=}}</ref> and was also based at [[Reading Gaol]], working for the [[Minister of Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Food]]. He became a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1942,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=35586 |page=2489 |supp=y | date=5 June 1942 }}</ref> and after the war, he worked at the [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Education]] (1945\u20131952), rising to [[Permanent Secretary]] and then the [[Ministry of Fuel and Power]] until 1958. He became a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in 1946,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=37598 |page=2759 | date=4 June 1946 |supp=y }}</ref> and was raised to a [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross]] in 1955.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=40366 | supp=y |page=3 | date=31 December 1954 }}</ref> ''Inter alia'', Maud appeared on the [[BBC]] programme ''[[The Brains Trust]]'' in 1958. He was [[High Commissioner]] to the [[Union of South Africa|Union]] of [[South Africa]] from 1959 to 1961, and Ambassador from 1961, when the country became a republic and left the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]. In 1963, he became Master of University College, Oxford, where he had been a Fellow before the Second World War.\n\n==The Maud Committee==\nIn March 1964, Maud was appointed by Sir [[Keith Joseph]], at the request of local council associations, to head a departmental committee looking into the management of local government. The Maud Committee reported three years later.<ref name=\"Maud Committee\">\"Management of Local Government\", Committee on the Management of Local Government, HMSO, 1967.</ref> During the course of the inquiry, Maud was chosen to head a [[Royal Commission]] on the reform of all [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local government in England]]. He was awarded a [[life peer]]age, hyphenating his surname<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=44349 |date=23 June 1967 |page=7032}}</ref> to become '''Baron Redcliffe-Maud''', of the City and County of [[Bristol]] in 1967.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=44362 |page=7641 | date=11 July 1967 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:England RedcliffeMaud.png|thumb|upright|Local government in England as proposed by the 1969 [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]].]]\n[[File:Entance to Redcliffe-Maud House, University College annex, Oxford.JPG|thumb|upright|Main entrance of the Redcliffe-Maud House at the [[University College, Oxford|University College]] annexe in [[North Oxford]].]]\n[[File:Redcliffe-Maud House, University College annex, Oxford.JPG|thumb|Redcliffe-Maud House in North Oxford, named in his honour.<ref name=\"stavertonia\" />]]\nThe Report of the Royal Commission on Local Government in England, popularly known as the [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]], was published in 1969. It advocated the wholesale reform of local council boundaries and the institution of large unitary councils based on the principle of mixing rural and urban areas. Accepted by the Labour government of [[Harold Wilson]] with minor changes, the opposition from rural areas convinced the Conservative opposition to oppose it and no further action was taken after the Conservatives won the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]].<ref name=\"Conservative reaction\">{{cite book| first=Bruce | last=Wood | title=The Process of Local Government Reform 1966\u201374 | publisher=[[George Allen & Unwin]] | year=1976 | pages=74\u201375 }}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\nHe retired as Master of University College in 1976, to be succeeded by the leading lawyer [[Lord Goodman]]. His 1973 portrait by [[Ruskin Spear]] can be seen in the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]], London.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp05691 | title=John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud | publisher=[[National Portrait Gallery, London]] | accessdate=6 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/john-primatt-redcliffe-maud-baron-redcliffe-maud-158003 |title=John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud by Ruskin Spear |access-date=19 January 2015 |publisher=[[Art UK]]}}</ref> Another portrait hangs in the Hall at University College in Oxford.\n\n==Family==\nRedcliffe-Maud was married to [[Jean Redcliffe-Maud|Jean Hamilton]], who was educated at [[Somerville College, Oxford]]. His son, [[Humphrey Maud]], was one of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s favourite boys while he was at Eton. Sir John intervened to curtail Humphrey's frequent visits to stay with Britten on his own. The incident is described in John Bridcut's ''[[Britten's Children]]''.\n\n==Death and legacy==\nJohn Redcliffe-Maud is buried in [[Holywell Cemetery]], [[Oxford]]. His archive is held by the [[London School of Economics]] Library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src |title=Redcliffe-Maud |access-date=6 December 2012 |website=LSE Archives |publisher=[[London School of Economics]]}}</ref> Redcliffe-Maud House at the [[University College, Oxford|University College]] annexe known as \"[[Stavertonia]]\" in [[North Oxford]] is named in honour of him.<ref name=\"stavertonia\">{{cite web | url=http://www.univ.ox.ac.uk/content/other-college-buildings-oxford | title=Other college buildings in Oxford: Stavertonia | publisher=[[University College, Oxford]] | accessdate=6 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116053956/http://www.univ.ox.ac.uk/content/other-college-buildings-oxford | archive-date=16 January 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* Redcliffe-Maud, John, ''Experiences of an Optimist: The Memoirs of John Redcliffe-Maud''. London: [[Hamish Hamilton]], 1981. ({{ISBN|0-241-10569-2}}.)<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v03/n14/ch-sisson/the-company-he-keeps | volume=3 | issue=14 | date=6 August 1981 | pages=15\u201316 | title=The company he keeps | first=C.H. | last=Sisson | journal=[[London Review of Books]] | accessdate=19 January 2015 }}</ref>\n* Redcliffe-Maud, Lord, & Wood, Bruce, ''English Local Government Reformed''. Oxford University Press, 1974. {{ISBN|0-198-88091-X}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|John Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31427|title=Maud, John Primatt Redcliffe, Baron Redcliffe-Maud (1906\u20131982)|last=Armstrong|first=Robert|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/31427|accessdate=30 May 2009}} {{ODNBsub}}\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=REDCLIFFE-MAUD Catalogue of the Redcliffe-Maud papers] at the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070618035533/http://www.lse.ac.uk/library/archive/Default.htm Archives Division] of the [[London School of Economics]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Maurice Gerald Holmes|Sir Maurice Holmes]] | as=Permanent Secretary of the <br /> [[Board of Education (United Kingdom)|Board of Education]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Permanent Secretary]] of the <br /> [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Education]] | years=1945\u20131952}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Gilbert Flemming]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Donald Fergusson|Sir Donald Fergusson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Permanent Secretary of the <br /> [[Ministry of Fuel and Power]] <br><small>([[Ministry of Power (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Power]] from 1957)</small> | years=1952\u20131958}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Dennis Proctor]]}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Percivale Liesching]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of High Commissioners from the United Kingdom to South Africa|British High Commissioner to <br /> South Africa]] | years=1959\u20131961}}\n{{s-aft | after=''<small>Himself as British Ambassador to South Africa</small>''}}\n{{s-bef | before=''<small>Himself as British High Commissioner to South Africa</small>''}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of High Commissioners from the United Kingdom to South Africa|British Ambassador to South Africa]] | years=1961\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Hugh Southern Stephenson|Sir Hugh Stephenson]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Arthur Lehman Goodhart|Arthur Goodhart]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Master of University College, Oxford]] | years=1963\u20131976}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Arnold Goodman, Baron Goodman|Arnold Goodman]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redcliffe-Maud, John}}\n[[Category:English civil servants]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors and High Commissioners of the United Kingdom to South Africa]]\n[[Category:Governors of Bechuanaland Protectorate]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bristol]]\n[[Category:People educated at Summer Fields School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellows of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Masters of Birkbeck, University of London]]\n[[Category:Life peers]]\n[[Category:Masters of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Permanent Secretaries of the Ministry of Education]]\n[[Category:Permanent Secretaries of the Ministry of Power]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Food]]\n[[Category:Civil servants in the Ministry of Reconstruction]]\n[[Category:1950s in Bechuanaland Protectorate]]\n[[Category:1960s in Bechuanaland Protectorate]]\n[[Category:1960s in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Burials at Holywell Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British civil servant and diplomat}}\n{{redirect|John Maud|the bishop|John Maud (bishop)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n__NOTOC__\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Lord Redcliffe-Maud\n|honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCB|CBE}}\n|image            = File:John Redcliffe-Maud.jpg\n|imagesize        = 180px\n|smallimage       = \n|caption          = Portrait of John Redcliffe-Maud.\n|birthname        = John Primatt Redcliffe Maud<!-- Unhyphenated at birth -->\n|birth_date       = {{birth date|1906|2|3|df=y}}\n|birth_place      = [[Bristol]], England\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|1982|11|20|1906|2|3|df=y}}\n|death_place      = [[Oxford]], England\n|restingplace     = [[Holywell Cemetery]], [[Oxford]], England\n|restingplacecoordinates =\n|nationality      = British\n|party            =\n|occupation       = civil servant\n}}\n\n'''John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCB|CBE}} (3 February 1906 \u2013 20 November 1982) was a British civil servant and diplomat.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.aim25.ac.uk/cgi-bin/vcdf/detail?coll_id=3814&inst_id=1 | title=Maud, John Primatt Redcliffe Redcliffe-, 1906\u20131982, Baron Redcliffe-Maud of Bristol, civil servant and diplomat | website=[[AIM25]] | location=UK | accessdate=19 January 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1093/ref:odnb/31427| title = The Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| year = 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Bristol]], Maud was educated at [[Eton College]] and [[New College, Oxford]]. He gained a Second in Classical Moderations in 1928 and a First in Literae Humaniores ('Greats') in 1928.<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1932'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1932, pp. 263, 312</ref> At [[University of Oxford|Oxford]] he was a member of the [[Oxford University Dramatic Society]] (OUDS). In 1928, he gained the one-year Henry P. Davison scholarship to [[Harvard University]]<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1932'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1932, p.344</ref> where he was awarded an A.B. in 1929.<ref name=\"Who's Who 1965\">''Who's Who, 1965'', London : A. & C. Black, 1965, p.2063</ref> From 1929 to 1932 he was a Junior Research Fellow [[University College, Oxford]] and from 1932-39 Fellow (Praelector in Politics)<ref>''Oxford University Calendar 1935'', Oxford : Oxford University Press, 1935, p.274</ref> and Dean of the college. He was awarded a Rhodes Travelling Scholarship to Africa in 1932 and held a University Lectureship in Politics at Oxford University, 1938-9.<ref name=\"Who's Who 1965\"/>\n\n==Civil service==\nDuring [[World War II]], he was [[Master (college)|Master]] of [[Birkbeck, University of London|Birkbeck College]] (1939\u20131943)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbk.ac.uk/about-us/past-officers |title=Prinicipals and Masters |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website=Birkbeck University of London |publisher= |access-date=3 October 2019 |quote=}}</ref> and was also based at [[Reading Gaol]], working for the [[Minister of Food (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Food]]. He became a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] in 1942,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=35586 |page=2489 |supp=y | date=5 June 1942 }}</ref> and after the war, he worked at the [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Education]] (1945\u20131952), rising to [[Permanent Secretary]] and then the [[Ministry of Fuel and Power]] until 1958. He became a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] in 1946,<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=37598 |page=2759 | date=4 June 1946 |supp=y }}</ref> and was raised to a [[Knight Grand Cross of the Order of the Bath|Knight Grand Cross]] in 1955.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=40366 | supp=y |page=3 | date=31 December 1954 }}</ref> ''Inter alia'', Maud appeared on the [[BBC]] programme ''[[The Brains Trust]]'' in 1958. He was [[High Commissioner]] to the [[Union of South Africa|Union]] of [[South Africa]] from 1959 to 1961, and Ambassador from 1961, when the country became a republic and left the [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]]. In 1963, he became Master of University College, Oxford, where he had been a Fellow before the Second World War.\n\n==The Maud Committee==\nIn March 1964, Maud was appointed by Sir [[Keith Joseph]], at the request of local council associations, to head a departmental committee looking into the management of local government. The Maud Committee reported three years later.<ref name=\"Maud Committee\">\"Management of Local Government\", Committee on the Management of Local Government, HMSO, 1967.</ref> During the course of the inquiry, Maud was chosen to head a [[Royal Commission]] on the reform of all [[Local government in the United Kingdom|local government in England]]. He was awarded a [[life peer]]age, hyphenating his surname<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=44349 |date=23 June 1967 |page=7032}}</ref> to become '''Baron Redcliffe-Maud''', of the City and County of [[Bristol]] in 1967.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=44362 |page=7641 | date=11 July 1967 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:England RedcliffeMaud.png|thumb|upright|Local government in England as proposed by the 1969 [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]].]]\n[[File:Entance to Redcliffe-Maud House, University College annex, Oxford.JPG|thumb|upright|Main entrance of the Redcliffe-Maud House at the [[University College, Oxford|University College]] annexe in [[North Oxford]].]]\n[[File:Redcliffe-Maud House, University College annex, Oxford.JPG|thumb|Redcliffe-Maud House in North Oxford, named in his honour.<ref name=\"stavertonia\" />]]\nThe Report of the Royal Commission on Local Government in England, popularly known as the [[Redcliffe-Maud Report]], was published in 1969. It advocated the wholesale reform of local council boundaries and the institution of large unitary councils based on the principle of mixing rural and urban areas. Accepted by the Labour government of [[Harold Wilson]] with minor changes, the opposition from rural areas convinced the Conservative opposition to oppose it and no further action was taken after the Conservatives won the [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970 general election]].<ref name=\"Conservative reaction\">{{cite book| first=Bruce | last=Wood | title=The Process of Local Government Reform 1966\u201374 | publisher=[[George Allen & Unwin]] | year=1976 | pages=74\u201375 }}</ref>\n\n==Retirement==\nHe retired as Master of University College in 1976, to be succeeded by the leading lawyer [[Lord Goodman]]. His 1973 portrait by [[Ruskin Spear]] can be seen in the [[National Portrait Gallery (London)|National Portrait Gallery]], London.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.npg.org.uk/live/search/person.asp?LinkID=mp05691 | title=John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud | publisher=[[National Portrait Gallery, London]] | accessdate=6 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/john-primatt-redcliffe-maud-baron-redcliffe-maud-158003 |title=John Primatt Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud by Ruskin Spear |access-date=19 January 2015 |publisher=[[Art UK]]}}</ref> Another portrait hangs in the Hall at University College in Oxford.\n\n==Family==\nRedcliffe-Maud was married to [[Jean Redcliffe-Maud|Jean Hamilton]], who was educated at [[Somerville College, Oxford]]. His son, [[Humphrey Maud]], was one of [[Benjamin Britten]]'s favourite boys while he was at Eton. Sir John intervened to curtail Humphrey's frequent visits to stay with Britten on his own. The incident is described in John Bridcut's ''[[Britten's Children]]''.\n\n==Death and legacy==\nJohn Redcliffe-Maud is buried in [[Holywell Cemetery]], [[Oxford]]. His archive is held by the [[London School of Economics]] Library.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src |title=Redcliffe-Maud |access-date=6 December 2012 |website=LSE Archives |publisher=[[London School of Economics]]}}</ref> Redcliffe-Maud House at the [[University College, Oxford|University College]] annexe known as \"[[Stavertonia]]\" in [[North Oxford]] is named in honour of him.<ref name=\"stavertonia\">{{cite web | url=http://www.univ.ox.ac.uk/content/other-college-buildings-oxford | title=Other college buildings in Oxford: Stavertonia | publisher=[[University College, Oxford]] | accessdate=6 December 2012 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116053956/http://www.univ.ox.ac.uk/content/other-college-buildings-oxford | archive-date=16 January 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n* Redcliffe-Maud, John, ''Experiences of an Optimist: The Memoirs of John Redcliffe-Maud''. London: [[Hamish Hamilton]], 1981. ({{ISBN|0-241-10569-2}}.)<ref>{{cite article| url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/v03/n14/ch-sisson/the-company-he-keeps | volume=3 | issue=14 | date=6 August 1981 | pages=15\u201316 | title=The company he keeps | first=C.H. | last=Sisson | journal=[[London Review of Books]] | accessdate=19 January 2015 }}</ref>\n* Redcliffe-Maud, Lord, & Wood, Bruce, ''English Local Government Reformed''. Oxford University Press, 1974. {{ISBN|0-198-88091-X}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|John Redcliffe-Maud, Baron Redcliffe-Maud}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31427|title=Maud, John Primatt Redcliffe, Baron Redcliffe-Maud (1906\u20131982)|last=Armstrong|first=Robert|work=[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/31427|accessdate=30 May 2009}} {{ODNBsub}}\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=REDCLIFFE-MAUD Catalogue of the Redcliffe-Maud papers] at the [https://web.archive.org/web/20070618035533/http://www.lse.ac.uk/library/archive/Default.htm Archives Division] of the [[London School of Economics]].\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Maurice Gerald Holmes|Sir Maurice Holmes]] | as=Permanent Secretary of the <br /> [[Board of Education (United Kingdom)|Board of Education]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Permanent Secretary]] of the <br /> [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Education]] | years=1945\u20131952}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Gilbert Flemming]]}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Donald Fergusson|Sir Donald Fergusson]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=Permanent Secretary of the <br /> [[Ministry of Fuel and Power]] <br><small>([[Ministry of Power (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Power]] from 1957)</small> | years=1952\u20131958}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Dennis Proctor]]}}\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Percivale Liesching]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of High Commissioners from the United Kingdom to South Africa|British High Commissioner to <br /> South Africa]] | years=1959\u20131961}}\n{{s-aft | after=''<small>Himself as British Ambassador to South Africa</small>''}}\n{{s-bef | before=''<small>Himself as British High Commissioner to South Africa</small>''}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[List of High Commissioners from the United Kingdom to South Africa|British Ambassador to South Africa]] | years=1961\u20131963}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Hugh Southern Stephenson|Sir Hugh Stephenson]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-